					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Alg=
orithm for computing greatest common divisors</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about an algorithm for the greatest common divisor. For the mathematics=
 of space, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry"=
 title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>. For other uses of "Eu=
clidean", see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_(disambigu=
ation)" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=3D"Euclidean (disambiguatio=
n)">Euclidean (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Not to be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_=
division" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Euclid%27s_algorithm_Book_VII=
_Proposition_2_3.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Euclid%27s_algorithm_Book_VI=
I_Proposition_2_3.svg/330px-Euclid%27s_algorithm_Book_VII_Proposition_2_3.s=
vg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"408" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"1098" data-file-height=3D"1495"></a><figcaption>E=
uclid's method for finding the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two startin=
g lengths BA and DC, both defined to be multiples of a common "unit" length=
. The length DC being shorter, it is used to "measure" BA, but only once be=
cause the remainder EA is less than DC. EA now measures (twice) the shorter=
 length DC, with remainder FC shorter than EA. Then FC measures (three time=
s) length EA. Because there is no remainder, the process ends with FC being=
 the GCD. On the right <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicomachus"=
 title=3D"Nicomachus">Nicomachus</a>'s example with numbers 49 and 21 resul=
ting in their GCD of 7 (derived from Heath 1908:300).</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>Euclidean algorithm</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_a=
lgorithm#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 1<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <b>Euclid's algorithm</b>, is an e=
fficient method for computing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Greatest_common_divisor" title=3D"Greatest common divisor">greatest common =
divisor</a> (GCD) of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integers"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integers">integers</a>, the largest number =
that divides them both without a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
emainder" title=3D"Remainder">remainder</a>. It is named after the ancient =
Greek <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician" title=3D"Math=
ematician">mathematician</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
d" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>, who first described it in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">hi=
s <i>Elements</i></a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-=
space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89300 BC</span>).
It is an example of an <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorith=
m" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a></i>, and is one of the oldest algorith=
ms in common use. It can be used to reduce <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fraction_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fraction (m=
athematics)">fractions</a> to their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Irreducible_fraction" title=3D"Irreducible fraction">simplest form</a>, a=
nd is a part of many other number-theoretic and cryptographic calculations.
</p><p>The Euclidean algorithm is based on the principle that the greatest =
common divisor of two numbers does not change if the larger number is repla=
ced by its difference with the smaller number. For example, <span class=3D"=
texhtml">21</span> is the GCD of <span class=3D"texhtml">252</span> and <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">105</span> (as <span class=3D"texhtml">252 =3D 21 =C3=
=97 12</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">105 =3D 21 =C3=97 5)</span>, and =
the same number <span class=3D"texhtml">21</span> is also the GCD of <span =
class=3D"texhtml">105</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">252 =E2=88=92 105 =
=3D 147</span>. Since this replacement reduces the larger of the two number=
s, repeating this process gives successively smaller pairs of numbers until=
 the two numbers become equal. When that occurs, that number is the GCD of =
the original two numbers. By <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
dean_algorithm#B%C3%A9zout's_identity">reversing the steps</a> or using the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm" tit=
le=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">extended Euclidean algorithm</a>, the G=
CD can be expressed as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_co=
mbination" title=3D"Linear combination">linear combination</a> of the two o=
riginal numbers, that is the sum of the two numbers, each multiplied by an =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer=
</a> (for example, <span class=3D"texhtml">21 =3D 5 =C3=97 105 + (=E2=88=92=
2) =C3=97 252</span>). The fact that the GCD can always be expressed in thi=
s way is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_=
identity" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's identity</a>.
</p><p>The version of the Euclidean algorithm described above=E2=80=94which=
 follows Euclid's original presentation=E2=80=94may require many subtractio=
n steps to find the GCD when one of the given numbers is much bigger than t=
he other. A more efficient version of the algorithm shortcuts these steps, =
instead replacing the larger of the two numbers by its remainder when divid=
ed by the smaller of the two (with this version, the algorithm stops when r=
eaching a zero remainder). With this improvement, the algorithm never requi=
res more steps than five times the number of digits (base 10) of the smalle=
r integer. This was proven by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabr=
iel_Lam%C3%A9" title=3D"Gabriel Lam=C3=A9">Gabriel Lam=C3=A9</a> in 1844 (<=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lam%C3%A9%E2%80%99s_Theorem" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lam=C3=A9=E2=80=99s Theorem">Lam=C3=A9's Theorem<=
/a>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean=
_algorithm#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and marks the beginning of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" title=3D"Com=
putational complexity theory">computational complexity theory</a>. Addition=
al methods for improving the algorithm's efficiency were developed in the 2=
0th century.
</p><p>The Euclidean algorithm has many theoretical and practical applicati=
ons. It is used for reducing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fract=
ion_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fraction (mathematics)">f=
ractions</a> to their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_=
fraction" title=3D"Irreducible fraction">simplest form</a> and for performi=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular arithmet=
ic</a>. Computations using this algorithm form part of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_protocol" title=3D"Cryptographic pro=
tocol">cryptographic protocols</a> that are used to secure <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet" title=3D"Internet">internet</a> communic=
ations, and in methods for breaking these cryptosystems by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Integer factorizat=
ion">factoring large composite numbers</a>. The Euclidean algorithm may be =
used to solve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equation=
" title=3D"Diophantine equation">Diophantine equations</a>, such as finding=
 numbers that satisfy multiple congruences according to the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem" title=3D"Chinese remai=
nder theorem">Chinese remainder theorem</a>, to construct <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_continued_fraction" title=3D"Simple continue=
d fraction">continued fractions</a>, and to find accurate <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_approximation" title=3D"Diophantine app=
roximation">rational approximations</a> to real numbers. Finally, it can be=
 used as a basic tool for proving theorems in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a> such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_four-square_theorem=
" title=3D"Lagrange's four-square theorem">Lagrange's four-square theorem</=
a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_=
arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmetic">uniqueness of prime=
 factorizations</a>.
</p><p>The original algorithm was described only for natural numbers and ge=
ometric lengths (real numbers), but the algorithm was generalized in the 19=
th century to other types of numbers, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integer" title=3D"Gaussian integer">Gaussian integers<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polyn=
omial">polynomials</a> of one variable. This led to modern <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abstr=
act algebraic</a> notions such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Euclidean_domain" title=3D"Euclidean domain">Euclidean domains</a>.
</p>
