<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Background:_greatest_common=
_divisor">Background: greatest common divisor</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Background: greatest common divisor"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divi=
sor" title=3D"Greatest common divisor">Greatest common divisor</a></div>
<p>The Euclidean algorithm calculates the greatest common divisor (GCD) of =
two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natur=
al number">natural numbers</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">b</span>. The greatest common divisor <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> is the largest natural number that =
divides both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>=
 without leaving a remainder. Synonyms for GCD include <i>greatest common f=
actor</i> (GCF), <i>highest common factor</i> (HCF), <i>highest common divi=
sor</i> (HCD), and <i>greatest common measure</i> (GCM). The greatest commo=
n divisor is often written as <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i=
>)</span> or, more simply, as <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>)<=
/span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although the la=
tter notation is ambiguous, also used for concepts such as an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theor=
y)">ideal</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_of_integ=
ers" title=3D"Ring of integers">ring of integers</a>, which is closely rela=
ted to GCD.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) =3D 1</span>, the=
n <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> are said t=
o be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coprime_integers" title=3D"Co=
prime integers">coprime</a> (or relatively prime).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algori=
thm#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> This property does not imply that <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> or <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> are themselves <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prim=
e numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For exam=
ple, <span class=3D"texhtml">6</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">35</span>=
 factor as <span class=3D"texhtml">6 =3D 2 =C3=97 3</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml">35 =3D 5 =C3=97 7</span>, so they are not prime, but their pri=
me factors are different, so <span class=3D"texhtml">6</span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">35</span> are coprime, with no common factors other than&nbs=
p;<span class=3D"texhtml">1</span>.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:24x60.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img=
 alt=3D"&quot;Tall, slender rectangle divided into a grid of squares. The r=
ectangle is two squares wide and five squares tall.&quot;" src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/24x60.svg/250px-24x60.svg.=
png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"470" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"1267"></a><figcaption>A 24=
=C3=9760 rectangle is covered with ten 12=C3=9712 square tiles, where 12 is=
 the GCD of 24 and 60. More generally, an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>=
=C3=97<i>b</i></span> rectangle can be covered with square tiles of side-le=
ngth <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> onl=
y if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> is =
a common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>)</span>.=
 Since <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> a=
nd <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> are b=
oth multiples of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
g</span>, they can be written <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>mg</i=
></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>b=
</i> =3D <i>ng</i></span>, and there is no larger number <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>G</i> &gt; <i>g</i></span> for which this is true. The natural num=
bers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> must be=
 coprime, since any common factor could be factored out of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> to make <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> greater. Thus, any other num=
ber <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> that=
 divides both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</=
span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span=
> must also divide <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">g</span>. The greatest common divisor <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">b</span> is the unique (positive) common divisor of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> that is divisible b=
y any other common divisor <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">c</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-7"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The greatest common divisor can be visualized as follows.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eu=
clidean_algorithm#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Consider a rectangular area <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> by <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and any common di=
visor <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> th=
at divides both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a=
</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</sp=
an> exactly. The sides of the rectangle can be divided into segments of len=
gth <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, whi=
ch divides the rectangle into a grid of squares of side length <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>. The GCD <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> is the largest val=
ue of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> fo=
r which this is possible. For illustration, a <span class=3D"texhtml">24=C3=
=9760</span> rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: <span class=3D=
"texhtml">1=C3=971</span> squares, <span class=3D"texhtml">2=C3=972</span> =
squares, <span class=3D"texhtml">3=C3=973</span> squares, <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">4=C3=974</span> squares, <span class=3D"texhtml">6=C3=976</span> squ=
ares or <span class=3D"texhtml">12=C3=9712</span> squares. Therefore, <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">12</span> is the GCD of <span class=3D"texhtml">24</span=
> and <span class=3D"texhtml">60</span>. A <span class=3D"texhtml">24=C3=97=
60</span> rectangular area can be divided into a grid of <span class=3D"tex=
html">12=C3=9712</span> squares, with two squares along one edge (<span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">24/12 =3D 2</span>) and five squares along the other (<span =
class=3D"texhtml">60/12 =3D 5</span>).
</p><p>The greatest common divisor of two numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is the product of the prime factors s=
hared by the two numbers, where each prime factor can be repeated as many t=
imes as it divides both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">b</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schroeder_21_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Schroeder=
_21-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> For example, since <span class=3D"texhtml">1386</span> ca=
n be factored into <span class=3D"texhtml">2 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 7 =C3=
=97 11</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">3213</span> can be factored into=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 7 =C3=97 17</span>, the=
 GCD of <span class=3D"texhtml">1386</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">321=
3</span> equals <span class=3D"texhtml">63 =3D 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 7</span>, =
the product of their shared prime factors (with 3 repeated since <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">3 =C3=97 3</span> divides both). If two numbers have no commo=
n prime factors, their GCD is <span class=3D"texhtml">1</span> (obtained he=
re as an instance of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empty_pro=
duct" title=3D"Empty product">empty product</a>); in other words, they are =
coprime. A key advantage of the Euclidean algorithm is that it can find the=
 GCD efficiently without having to compute the prime factors.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
idean_algorithm#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_facto=
rization" title=3D"Integer factorization">Factorization</a> of large intege=
rs is believed to be a computationally very difficult problem, and the secu=
rity of many widely used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptogra=
phic_protocol" title=3D"Cryptographic protocol">cryptographic protocols</a>=
 is based upon its infeasibility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schroeder_216_12-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algori=
thm#cite_note-Schroeder_216-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another definition of the GCD is helpful in advanced mathematics, pa=
rticularly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_theory" title=3D"R=
ing theory">ring theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Leveque_p33_13-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cit=
e_note-Leveque_p33-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The greatest common divisor <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> of two nonzero num=
bers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is also=
 their smallest positive integral linear combination, that is, the smallest=
 positive number of the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ua</i> + <i>vb</i><=
/span> where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v</span>=
 are integers. The set of all integral linear combinations of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is actually the same as=
 the set of all multiples of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">g</span> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">mg</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">m</span> is an integer). In modern mathematical language, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring=
 theory)">ideal</a> generated by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">b</span> is the ideal generated by&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> alone (an ideal generated by a =
single element is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princip=
al_ideal" title=3D"Principal ideal">principal ideal</a>, and all ideals of =
the integers are principal ideals). Some properties of the GCD are in fact =
easier to see with this description, for instance the fact that any common =
divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</spa=
n> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> a=
lso divides the GCD (it divides both terms of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ua=
</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;<i>vb</i></span>). The equivalence of this GCD definition =
with the other definitions is described below.
</p><p>The GCD of three or more numbers equals the product of the prime fac=
tors common to all the numbers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-14">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> but it can also be calculated by repeatedly taking the GCDs of =
pairs of numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-15"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Fo=
r example,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, <i>c</i>) =3D gcd(<=
i>a</i>, gcd(<i>b</i>, <i>c</i>)) =3D gcd(gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>), <i>c</i>=
) =3D gcd(gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>c</i>), <i>b</i>).</span></dd></dl>
<p>Thus, Euclid's algorithm, which computes the GCD of two integers, suffic=
es to calculate the GCD of arbitrarily many integers.
</p>
