<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_of_validity">Proof of=
 validity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEu=
clidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Proof of validity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The validity of the Euclidean algorithm can be proven by a two-step argu=
ment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the first s=
tep, the final nonzero remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N<=
/i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> is shown to divide both <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>a</i></span> and&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>. Since it =
is a common divisor, it must be less than or equal to the greatest common d=
ivisor&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>. In the second step, it=
 is shown that any common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span=
> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>, including&nbsp;<span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>, must divide <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><=
sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>; therefore, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
g</i></span> must be less than or equal to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i>=
<sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. These two opposite inequalities imply=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub> =3D <i>g</i>=
</span>.
</p><p>To demonstrate that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub></span> divides both <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> a=
nd <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> (the first step), <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> divides its predeces=
sor <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <=
i>q</i><sub><i>N</i></sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span></dd=
></dl>
<p>since the final remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i><=
/sub></span> is zero. <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=
=921</sub></span> also divides its next predecessor <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub></span>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub> =3D <=
i>q</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =
+ <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span></dd></dl>
<p>because it divides both terms on the right-hand side of the equation. It=
erating the same argument, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub></span> divides all the preceding remainders, including <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></spa=
n>. None of the preceding remainders <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><=
i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</=
i>=E2=88=923</sub></span>, etc. divide <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></sp=
an> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>, since they leave a remaind=
er. Since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></sp=
an> is a common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and&nbsp=
;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><=
sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub> =E2=89=A4 <i>g</i></span>.
</p><p>In the second step, any natural number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c<=
/i></span> that divides both <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> (in other words, any common divisor o=
f <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b<=
/i></span>) divides the remainders <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>=
k</i></sub></span>. By definition, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> =
and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> can be written as multiples of =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i></span>: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =
=3D <i>mc</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D <i>nc</i></sp=
an>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>n</i></span> are natural numbers. Therefore, <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>c</i></span> divides the initial remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r=
</i><sub>0</sub></span>, since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>=
 =3D <i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub>0</sub><i>b</i> =3D <i>mc</i> =E2=88=
=92 <i>q</i><sub>0</sub><i>nc</i> =3D (<i>m</i> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub>0</s=
ub><i>n</i>)<i>c</i></span>. An analogous argument shows that <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i></span> also divides the subsequent remainders <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r<=
/i><sub>2</sub></span>, etc. Therefore, the greatest common divisor <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> must divide <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</=
i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>, which implies that <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>g</i> =E2=89=A4 <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. Si=
nce the first part of the argument showed the reverse (<span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub> =E2=89=A4 <i>g</i></span>), it fo=
llows that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=
=921</sub></span>. Thus, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> is the gre=
atest common divisor of all the succeeding pairs:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algori=
thm#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lovasz_2003_19-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#ci=
te_note-Lovasz_2003-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
