<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Worked_example">Worked exam=
ple</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidea=
n_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Worke=
d example"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Euclidean_algorithm_1071_462.gif" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img alt=3D"Animation in which progressively smaller squ=
are tiles are added to cover a rectangle completely." src=3D"https://upload=
.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Euclidean_algorithm_1071_462.gi=
f/250px-Euclidean_algorithm_1071_462.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" =
height=3D"440" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"462" data-file-=
height=3D"1071"></a><figcaption>Subtraction-based animation of the Euclidea=
n algorithm. The initial rectangle has dimensions <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>a</i> =3D 1071</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D 462</span>=
. Squares of size <span class=3D"texhtml">462=C3=97462</span> are placed wi=
thin it leaving a <span class=3D"texhtml">462=C3=97147</span> rectangle. Th=
is rectangle is tiled with <span class=3D"texhtml">147=C3=97147</span> squa=
res until a <span class=3D"texhtml">21=C3=97147</span> rectangle is left, w=
hich in turn is tiled with <span class=3D"texhtml">21=C3=9721</span> square=
s, leaving no uncovered area. The smallest square size, <span class=3D"texh=
tml">21</span>, is the GCD of <span class=3D"texhtml">1071</span> and <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">462</span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>For illustration, the Euclidean algorithm can be used to find the greate=
st common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D 1071</span> and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D 462</span>. To begin, multiples of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml">462</span> are subtracted from <span class=3D"texhtml">=
1071</span> until the remainder is less than <span class=3D"texhtml">462</s=
pan>. Two such multiples can be subtracted (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i=
><sub>0</sub> =3D 2</span>), leaving a remainder of <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>147</span>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">1071 =3D 2 =C3=97 462 + 147</span>.</dd></d=
l>
<p>Then multiples of <span class=3D"texhtml">147</span> are subtracted from=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">462</span> until the remainder is less than <span =
class=3D"texhtml">147</span>. Three multiples can be subtracted (<span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>1</sub> =3D 3</span>), leaving a remainder of <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">21</span>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">462 =3D 3 =C3=97 147 + 21</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Then multiples of <span class=3D"texhtml">21</span> are subtracted from =
<span class=3D"texhtml">147</span> until the remainder is less than <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">21</span>. Seven multiples can be subtracted (<span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>2</sub> =3D 7</span>), leaving no remainder:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">147 =3D 7 =C3=97 21 + 0</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Since the last remainder is zero, the algorithm ends with <span class=3D=
"texhtml">21</span> as the greatest common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">1071</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">462</span>. This agrees with the=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(1071, 462)</span> found by prime factorization=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#Background:_g=
reatest_common_divisor">above</a>. In tabular form, the steps are:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" id=3D"basic_Euclidean_algorithm" style=3D"margin=
-left:auto; margin-right:auto; text-align:center">

<tbody><tr>
<th>Step <i>k</i></th>
<th>Equation</th>
<th>Quotient and remainder
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>0</td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml">1071 =3D <i>q</i><sub>0</sub> 462 + <i>r</i><su=
b>0</sub></span></td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>0</sub> =3D 2</span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub> =3D 147</span>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml">462 =3D <i>q</i><sub>1</sub> 147 + <i>r</i><sub=
>1</sub></span></td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>1</sub> =3D 3</span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub> =3D 21</span>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml">147 =3D <i>q</i><sub>2</sub> 21 + <i>r</i><sub>=
2</sub></span></td>
<td><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>2</sub> =3D 7</span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>2</sub> =3D 0</span>; algorithm ends
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Visualization">Visualizatio=
n</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_=
algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Visuali=
zation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>The Euclidean algorithm can be visualized in terms of the tiling analogy=
 given above for the greatest common divisor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kimberling=
_1983_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eu=
clidean_algorithm#cite_note-Kimberling_1983-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Assume that we =
wish to cover an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>=C3=97<i>b</i></span> rect=
angle with square tiles exactly, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></sp=
an> is the larger of the two numbers. We first attempt to tile the rectangl=
e using <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>=C3=97<i>b</i></span> square tiles;=
 however, this leaves an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>=C3=97=
<i>b</i></span> residual rectangle untiled, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>r</i><sub>0</sub> &lt; <i>b</i></span>. We then attempt to tile the resid=
ual rectangle with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>=C3=97<i>r</=
i><sub>0</sub></span> square tiles. This leaves a second residual rectangle=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub>=C3=97<i>r</i><sub>0</sub></sp=
an>, which we attempt to tile using <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1<=
/sub>=C3=97<i>r</i><sub>1</sub></span> square tiles, and so on. The sequenc=
e ends when there is no residual rectangle, i.e., when the square tiles cov=
er the previous residual rectangle exactly. The length of the sides of the =
smallest square tile is the GCD of the dimensions of the original rectangle=
. For example, the smallest square tile in the adjacent figure is <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">21=C3=9721</span> (shown in red), and <span class=3D"texhtml=
">21</span> is the GCD of <span class=3D"texhtml">1071</span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">462</span>, the dimensions of the original rectangle (shown =
in green).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Euclidean_division">Euclide=
an division</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Euclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Euclidean division"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" =
title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a></div>
<p>At every step <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>, the Euclidean alg=
orithm computes a quotient <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></s=
ub></span> and remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub=
></span> from two numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=
=88=922</sub></span>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <=
i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i>r</i>=
<sub><i>k</i></sub></span>,</dd></dl>
<p>where the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> is =
non-negative and is strictly less than the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a> of <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. The theo=
rem which underlies the definition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division=
</a> ensures that such a quotient and remainder always exist and are unique=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In Euclid's original version of the algorithm, the quotient and rema=
inder are found by repeated subtraction; that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> is subtracted from <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span> repeatedly until =
the remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> is=
 smaller than <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>=
</span>. After that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></sp=
an> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span=
> are exchanged and the process is iterated. Euclidean division reduces all=
 the steps between two exchanges into a single step, which is thus more eff=
icient. Moreover, the quotients are not needed, thus one may replace Euclid=
ean division by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulo_operati=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Modulo operation">modulo operation</a>, =
which gives only the remainder. Thus the iteration of the Euclidean algorit=
hm becomes simply
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>r</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> mod <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>=
.</dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Implementations">Implementa=
tions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclid=
ean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Imp=
lementations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Implementations of the algorithm may be expressed in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudocode" title=3D"Pseudocode">pseudocode</a>. For =
example, the division-based version may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Computer_programming" title=3D"Computer programming">programmed</a=
> as<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<pre><b>function</b> gcd(a, b)
    <b>while</b> b =E2=89=A0 0
        t&nbsp;:=3D b
        b&nbsp;:=3D a <b>mod</b> b
        a&nbsp;:=3D t
    <b>return</b> a
</pre>
<p>At the beginning of the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>th iterat=
ion, the variable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> holds the latest =
remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></sp=
an>, whereas the variable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> holds its=
 predecessor, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub>=
</span>. The step <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>&nbsp;:=3D <i>a</i> mod <=
i>b</i></span> is equivalent to the above recursion formula <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =E2=89=A1 <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=
=922</sub> mod <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. The <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_variable" title=3D"Temporary varia=
ble">temporary variable</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> holds t=
he value of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></=
span> while the next remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i=
></sub></span> is being calculated. At the end of the loop iteration, the v=
ariable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> holds the remainder <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>, whereas the variable <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> holds its predecessor, <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>.
</p><p>(If negative inputs are allowed, or if the <code><b>mod</b></code> f=
unction may return negative values, the last line must be replaced with <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap"><code><b>return abs</b>(a)</code></span>.)
</p><p>In the subtraction-based version, which was Euclid's original versio=
n, the remainder calculation (<span class=3D"nowrap"><code>b&nbsp;:=3D a <b=
>mod</b> b</code></span>) is replaced by repeated subtraction.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lidean_algorithm#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Contrary to the division-based v=
ersion, which works with arbitrary integers as input, the subtraction-based=
 version supposes that the input consists of positive integers and stops wh=
en <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i></span>:
</p>
<pre><b>function</b> gcd(a, b)
    <b>while</b> a =E2=89=A0 b=20
        <b>if</b> a &gt; b
            a&nbsp;:=3D a =E2=88=92 b
        <b>else</b>
            b&nbsp;:=3D b =E2=88=92 a
    <b>return</b> a
</pre>
<p>The variables <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> alternate holding the previous remainders <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span>. Assume that <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is larger than <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>b</i></span> at the beginning of an iteration; then <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>a</i></span> equals <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=
=E2=88=922</sub></span>, since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i=
>=E2=88=922</sub> &gt; <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. During=
 the loop iteration, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is reduced by =
multiples of the previous remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>=
 until <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is smaller than <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>. Then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> =
is the next remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></=
span>. Then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> is reduced by multiples=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> until it is again smaller than =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>, giving the next remainder <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>+1</sub></span>, and so on.
</p><p>The recursive version<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-24"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> is based on the equality of the GCDs of successive remainders and =
the stopping condition <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub>, 0) =3D <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>.
</p>
<pre><b>function</b> gcd(a, b)
    <b>if</b> b =3D 0
        <b>return</b> a
    <b>else</b>
        <b>return</b> gcd(b, a <b>mod</b> b)
</pre>
<p>(As above, if negative inputs are allowed, or if the <code><b>mod</b></c=
ode> function may return negative values, the instruction <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><code><b>return</b> a</code></span> must be replaced by <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><code><b>return max</b>(a, =E2=88=92a)</code></span>.)
</p><p>For illustration, the <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(1071, 462)</span> =
is calculated from the equivalent <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(462, 1071 mod=
 462) =3D gcd(462, 147)</span>. The latter GCD is calculated from the <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">gcd(147, 462 mod 147) =3D gcd(147, 21)</span>, which in =
turn is calculated from the <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(21, 147 mod 21) =3D=
 gcd(21, 0) =3D 21</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Method_of_least_absolute_re=
mainders">Method of least absolute remainders</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Method of least absolute remainders"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>In another version of Euclid's algorithm, the quotient at each step is i=
ncreased by one if the resulting negative remainder is smaller in magnitude=
 than the typical positive remainder.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ore_least_abs_rema=
inders_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Ore_least_abs_remainders-25"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Stewart_1964_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stewart_1964-26"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Previously, the equation
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <=
i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i>r</i>=
<sub><i>k</i></sub></span></dd></dl>
<p>assumed that <span class=3D"texhtml">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"pa=
dding-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</su=
b></span>| &gt; <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> &gt; 0</span>. However, an alte=
rnative negative remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i><sub><i>k</i></s=
ub></span> can be computed:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D (=
<i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> + 1) <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i=
>e</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span></dd></dl>
<p>if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>&nbsp;&g=
t;&nbsp;0</span> or
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D (=
<i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =E2=80=93 1) <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</s=
ub> + <i>e</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span></dd></dl>
<p>if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>&nbsp;&l=
t;&nbsp;0</span>.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> is rep=
laced by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>. when <=
span class=3D"texhtml">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em;=
 padding-right:0.1em;"><i>e</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>| &lt; |<span clas=
s=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>r</i><su=
b><i>k</i></sub></span>|</span>, then one gets a variant of Euclidean algor=
ithm such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-le=
ft:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>| =E2=89=
=A4 |<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1e=
m;"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>| / 2</span></dd></dl>
<p>at each step.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leopold_Kronecker" title=3D=
"Leopold Kronecker">Leopold Kronecker</a> has shown that this version requi=
res the fewest steps of any version of Euclid's algorithm.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Ore_least_abs_remainders_25-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Ore_least_abs_remainders-=
25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stewart_1964_26-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stewa=
rt_1964-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> More generally, it has been proven that, for every =
input numbers <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>, the number of steps is minimal if and =
only if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> is chose=
n in order that <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle \left|{\frac {r_{k+1}}{r_{k}}}\right|&lt;{\frac {1}{\varphi }}\si=
m 0.618,}">
