<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Historical_development">His=
torical development</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Historical development"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Euklid.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><im=
g alt=3D"&quot;Depiction of Euclid as a bearded man holding a pair of divid=
ers to a tablet.&quot;" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/9/9e/Euklid.jpg/250px-Euklid.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190"=
 height=3D"328" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"725" data-file=
-height=3D"1253"></a><figcaption>The Euclidean algorithm was probably inven=
ted before <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid=
">Euclid</a>, depicted here holding a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Compass_(drawing_tool)" title=3D"Compass (drawing tool)">compass</a> in=
 a painting of about 1474.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The Euclidean algorithm is one of the oldest algorithms in common use.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._318_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._318-28"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> It appears in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_=
Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Euclid's <i>Elements</i></a> (c.&nbsp=
;300&nbsp;BC), specifically in Book&nbsp;7 (Propositions 1=E2=80=932) and B=
ook&nbsp;10 (Propositions 2=E2=80=933). In Book&nbsp;7, the algorithm is fo=
rmulated for integers, whereas in Book&nbsp;10, it is formulated for length=
s of line segments. (In modern usage, one would say it was formulated there=
 for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real nu=
mber">real numbers</a>. But lengths, areas, and volumes, represented as rea=
l numbers in modern usage, are not measured in the same units and there is =
no natural unit of length, area, or volume; the concept of real numbers was=
 unknown at that time.) The latter algorithm is geometrical. The GCD of two=
 lengths <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>b</i></span> corresponds to the greatest length <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>g</i></span> that measures <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> evenly; in other words, the length=
s <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b<=
/i></span> are both integer multiples of the length <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>g</i></span>.
</p><p>The algorithm was probably not discovered by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>, who compiled results=
 from earlier mathematicians in his <i>Elements</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wei=
l_1983_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Weil_1983-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-J=
ones_1994_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Jones_1994-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The mathematicia=
n and historian <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bartel_Leendert_va=
n_der_Waerden" title=3D"Bartel Leendert van der Waerden">B. L. van der Waer=
den</a> suggests that Book VII derives from a textbook on <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theor=
y</a> written by mathematicians in the school of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-van_der_Waerden_1954_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-van_der_Waerden_1954-31"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> The algorithm was probably known by <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Eudoxus_of_Cnidus" title=3D"Eudoxus of Cnidus">Eudoxus of Cn=
idus</a> (about 375 BC).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._318_28-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-Knuth,_p._318-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note=
-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> The algorithm may even pre-date Eudoxus,<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidea=
n_algorithm#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_not=
e-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> judging from the use of the technical term =E1=BC=80=CE=
=BD=CE=B8=CF=85=CF=86=CE=B1=CE=AF=CF=81=CE=B5=CF=83=CE=B9=CF=82 (<i>anthyph=
airesis</i>, reciprocal subtraction) in works by Euclid and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Claude Brezinski, follo=
wing remarks by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pappus_of_Alexandr=
ia" title=3D"Pappus of Alexandria">Pappus of Alexandria</a>, credits the al=
gorithm to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theaetetus_(mathematici=
an)" title=3D"Theaetetus (mathematician)">Theaetetus</a> (c. 417 =E2=80=93 =
c. 369 BC).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Centuries later, Euclid's algorithm was discovered independently bot=
h in India and in China,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stillwell,_p._31_37-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#ci=
te_note-Stillwell,_p._31-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> primarily to solve <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equation" title=3D"Diophantine equati=
on">Diophantine equations</a> that arose in astronomy and making accurate c=
alendars. In the late 5th century, the Indian mathematician and astronomer =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhata" title=3D"Aryabhata">Ary=
abhata</a> described the algorithm as the "pulverizer",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Tattersall,_p._70_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Tattersall,_p._70-38"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 perhaps because of its effectiveness in solving Diophantine equations.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Although a special case=
 of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem"=
 title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese remainder theorem</a> had alre=
ady been described in the Chinese book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Sunzi_Suanjing" title=3D"Sunzi Suanjing">Sunzi Suanjing</a></i>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the general solution w=
as published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin_Jiushao" title=
=3D"Qin Jiushao">Qin Jiushao</a> in his 1247 book <i>Shushu Jiuzhang</i> (=
=E6=95=B8=E6=9B=B8=E4=B9=9D=E7=AB=A0 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematical_Treatise_in_Nine_Sections" title=3D"Mathematical Treatis=
e in Nine Sections">Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections</a></i>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Euclidean algorithm wa=
s first described <i>numerically</i> and popularized in Europe in the secon=
d edition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Gaspard_Bachet=
_de_M%C3%A9ziriac" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Claude Gaspard Bachet de =
M=C3=A9ziriac">Bachet's</a> <i>Probl=C3=A8mes plaisants et d=C3=A9lectables=
</i> (<i>Pleasant and enjoyable problems</i>, 1624).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tat=
tersall,_p._70_38-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Tattersall,_p._70-38"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In E=
urope, it was likewise used to solve Diophantine equations and in developin=
g <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_continued_fraction" title=
=3D"Simple continued fraction">continued fractions</a>. The <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm" title=3D"Extended E=
uclidean algorithm">extended Euclidean algorithm</a> was published by the E=
nglish mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Saun=
derson" title=3D"Nicholas Saunderson">Nicholas Saunderson</a>,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lidean_algorithm#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> who attributed it to <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Cotes" title=3D"Roger Cotes">Roger Cote=
s</a> as a method for computing continued fractions efficiently.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm led to the development =
of new number systems, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gau=
ssian_integer" title=3D"Gaussian integer">Gaussian integers</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eisenstein_integer" title=3D"Eisenstein i=
nteger">Eisenstein integers</a>. In 1815, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Gauss</a>=
 used the Euclidean algorithm to demonstrate unique factorization of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integer" title=3D"Gaussian inte=
ger">Gaussian integers</a>, although his work was first published in 1832.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gauss_1832_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Gauss_1832-44"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Gauss mentioned the algorithm in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Disquisitiones_Arithmeticae" title=3D"Disquisitiones Arithmeticae=
">Disquisitiones Arithmeticae</a></i> (published 1801), but only as a metho=
d for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continued_fraction" title=3D=
"Continued fraction">continued fractions</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stillwell,=
_p._31_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stillwell,_p._31-37"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Gustav_Lejeune_Dirichlet" title=3D"Peter =
Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet">Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet</a> seems to have =
been the first to describe the Euclidean algorithm as the basis for much of=
 number theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Leje=
une Dirichlet noted that many results of number theory, such as unique fact=
orization, would hold true for any other system of numbers to which the Euc=
lidean algorithm could be applied.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-4=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Lejeune Dirichlet's lectures on number theory were edited an=
d extended by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" ti=
tle=3D"Richard Dedekind">Richard Dedekind</a>, who used Euclid's algorithm =
to study <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_integer" title=
=3D"Algebraic integer">algebraic integers</a>, a new general type of number=
. For example, Dedekind was the first to prove <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_theorem_on_sums_of_two_squares" title=3D"Fermat's t=
heorem on sums of two squares">Fermat's two-square theorem</a> using the un=
ique factorization of Gaussian integers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Dedekind also defined the concept of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_domain" title=3D"Euclidean domain">Eucl=
idean domain</a>, a number system in which a generalized version of the Euc=
lidean algorithm can be defined (as described <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#Euclidean_domains">below</a>). In the closi=
ng decades of the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm gradually became ec=
lipsed by Dedekind's more general theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theory)">ideals</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<table class=3D"toccolours" style=3D"float: left; margin-left: 1em; margin-=
right: 1em; font-size: 85%; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 25%;" cells=
pacing=3D"5">
<tbody><tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;">
<p>"[The Euclidean algorithm] is the granddaddy of all algorithms, because =
it is the oldest nontrivial algorithm that has survived to the present day.=
"
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Do=
nald_Knuth" title=3D"Donald Knuth">Donald Knuth</a>, <i>The Art of Computer=
 Programming, Vol. 2: Seminumerical Algorithms</i>, 2nd edition (1981), p.&=
nbsp;318.
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Other applications of Euclid's algorithm were developed in the 19th cent=
ury. In 1829, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Charles_Fran=
%C3%A7ois_Sturm" title=3D"Jacques Charles Fran=C3=A7ois Sturm">Charles Stur=
m</a> showed that the algorithm was useful in the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Sturm%27s_theorem" title=3D"Sturm's theorem">Sturm chain</a=
> method for counting the real roots of polynomials in any given interval.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Euclidean algorithm was the first <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Integer_relation_algorithm" title=3D"Integer relation algorithm"=
>integer relation algorithm</a>, which is a method for finding integer rela=
tions between commensurate real numbers. Several novel <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_relation_algorithm" title=3D"Integer relation =
algorithm">integer relation algorithms</a> have been developed, such as the=
 algorithm of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helaman_Ferguson" ti=
tle=3D"Helaman Ferguson">Helaman Ferguson</a> and R.W. Forcade (1979)<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lenstra%E2%80%93Lenstra%E2%80%93Lov%C3%A1sz_lattice=
_basis_reduction_algorithm" title=3D"Lenstra=E2=80=93Lenstra=E2=80=93Lov=C3=
=A1sz lattice basis reduction algorithm">LLL algorithm</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid=
ean_algorithm#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_n=
ote-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1969, Cole and Davie developed a two-player game based on the Euc=
lidean algorithm, called <i>The Game of Euclid</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algo=
rithm#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which has an optimal strategy.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lidean_algorithm#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The players begin with two piles=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
b</i></span> stones. The players take turns removing <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>m</i></span> multiples of the smaller pile from the larger. Thus, if t=
he two piles consist of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span> stones, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x=
</i></span> is larger than <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span>, the nex=
t player can reduce the larger pile from <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></=
span> stones to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=92 <i>my</i></span>=
 stones, as long as the latter is a nonnegative integer. The winner is the =
first player to reduce one pile to zero stones.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorith=
m#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-56"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mathematical_applications">=
Mathematical applications</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Mathematical applications"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"B=C3=A9zout's_identity"><sp=
an id=3D"B.C3.A9zout.27s_identity"></span>B=C3=A9zout's identity</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: B=C3=A9zout's iden=
tity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_iden=
tity" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's identity</a></div>
<p>B=C3=A9zout's identity states that the greatest common divisor <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> of two integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> can be represented =
as a linear sum of the original two numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i=
></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_al=
gorithm#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other words, it is always possible to =
find integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>t</i></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D <i>sa=
</i> + <i>tb</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-58"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> can be calculated from the quotients <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>0</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i=
><sub>1</sub></span>, etc. by reversing the order of equations in Euclid's =
algorithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Beginning=
 with the next-to-last equation, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> ca=
n be expressed in terms of the quotient <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><su=
b><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> and the two preceding remainders, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub></span>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=92=
1</sub> =3D <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i=
>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span>.</dd></=
dl>
<p>Those two remainders can be likewise expressed in terms of their quotien=
ts and preceding remainders,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <=
i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=924</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=
=922</sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub></span> and</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923</sub> =3D <i>r<=
/i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=925</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=923<=
/sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=924</sub></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Substituting these formulae for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>=
N</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N<=
/i>=E2=88=923</sub></span> into the first equation yields <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>g</i></span> as a linear sum of the remainders <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=924</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=925</sub></span>. The process of substituti=
ng remainders by formulae involving their predecessors can be continued unt=
il the original numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> are reached:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>2</sub> =3D <i>r</i><sub>0</su=
b> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub>2</sub> <i>r</i><sub>1</sub></span></dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub> =3D <i>b</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=
q</i><sub>1</sub> <i>r</i><sub>0</sub></span></dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub> =3D <i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=
q</i><sub>0</sub> <i>b</i></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>After all the remainders <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub></s=
pan>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub></span>, etc. have been s=
ubstituted, the final equation expresses <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></=
span> as a linear sum of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>, so that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>=
 =3D <i>sa</i> + <i>tb</i></span>.
</p><p>The Euclidean algorithm, and thus B=C3=A9zout's identity, can be gen=
eralized to the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclide=
an_domain" title=3D"Euclidean domain">Euclidean domains</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Principal_ideals_and_relate=
d_problems">Principal ideals and related problems</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Principal ideals and related prob=
lems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>B=C3=A9zout's identity provides yet another definition of the greatest c=
ommon divisor <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> of two numbers <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></spa=
n>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Leveque_p33_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Leveque_p33-13"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Consider the set of all numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ua</i>=
 + <i>vb</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i></span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i></span> are any two integers. Since <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> ar=
e both divisible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>, every number i=
n the set is divisible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>. In other=
 words, every number of the set is an integer multiple of <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>g</i></span>. This is true for every common divisor of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>. =
However, unlike other common divisors, the greatest common divisor is a mem=
ber of the set; by B=C3=A9zout's identity, choosing <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>u</i> =3D <i>s</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i> =3D <i>t=
</i></span> gives <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>. A smaller common=
 divisor cannot be a member of the set, since every member of the set must =
be divisible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>. Conversely, any mu=
ltiple <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>g</i></span> can be obtained by choosing <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>=
 =3D <i>ms</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i> =3D <i>mt</i></s=
pan>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>t</i></span> are the integers of B=C3=A9zout's identity. This may b=
e seen by multiplying B=C3=A9zout's identity by <i>m</i>,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>mg</i> =3D <i>msa</i> + <i>mtb</i></span=
>.</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, the set of all numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ua</i> + <i=
>vb</i></span> is equivalent to the set of multiples <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>m</i></span> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>. In other word=
s, the set of all possible sums of integer multiples of two numbers (<span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></spa=
n>) is equivalent to the set of multiples of <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i=
>a</i>, <i>b</i>)</span>. The GCD is said to be the generator of the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (rin=
g theory)">ideal</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>. This GCD definition led to the modern <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract a=
lgebra">abstract algebraic</a> concepts of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Principal_ideal" title=3D"Principal ideal">principal ideal</a> (=
an ideal generated by a single element) and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal_domain" title=3D"Principal ideal domain">princi=
pal ideal domain</a> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(ri=
ng_theory)" title=3D"Domain (ring theory)">domain</a> in which every ideal =
is a principal ideal).
</p><p>Certain problems can be solved using this result.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean=
_algorithm#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, consider two measuring cu=
ps of volume <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>b</i></span>. By adding/subtracting <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</=
i></span> multiples of the first cup and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i></=
span> multiples of the second cup, any volume <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ua=
</i> + <i>vb</i></span> can be measured out. These volumes are all multiple=
s of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D gcd(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>)</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Extended_Euclidean_algorith=
m">Extended Euclidean algorithm</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Extended Euclidean algorithm"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_a=
lgorithm" title=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">Extended Euclidean algorit=
hm</a></div>
<p>The integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>t</i></span> of B=C3=A9zout's identity can be computed efficien=
tly using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_a=
lgorithm" title=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">extended Euclidean algorit=
hm</a>. This extension adds two recursive equations to Euclid's algorithm<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>s</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub><i>s</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span></dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>t</i><sub><i=
>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub><i>t</i><sub><i=
>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span></dd></dl>
<p>with the starting values
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i><sub>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D 1, <i>t</=
i><sub>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D 0</span></dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i><sub>=E2=88=921</sub> =3D 0, <i>t</i><s=
ub>=E2=88=921</sub> =3D 1</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Using this recursion, B=C3=A9zout's integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
s</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> are given by <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i> =3D <i>s</i><sub><i>N</i></sub></span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i> =3D <i>t</i><sub><i>N</i></sub></span>, where =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i> + 1</span> is the step on which the algori=
thm terminates with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>+1</sub> =
=3D 0</span>.
</p><p>The validity of this approach can be shown by induction. Assume that=
 the recursion formula is correct up to step <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</=
i> =E2=88=92 1</span> of the algorithm; in other words, assume that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> =3D <i>s</i><su=
b><i>j</i></sub> <i>a</i> + <i>t</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> <i>b</i></span></dd=
></dl>
<p>for all <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>j</i></span> less than <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>. The <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>th st=
ep of the algorithm gives the equation
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>r</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub><i>r</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Since the recursion formula has been assumed to be correct for <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>, they may be expr=
essed in terms of the corresponding <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span>=
 and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> variables
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D (<i>s</i><s=
ub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> <i>a</i> + <i>t</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub=
> <i>b</i>) =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>(<i>s</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub> <i>a</i> + <i>t</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> <i>b</i>)</s=
pan>.</dd></dl>
<p>Rearranging this equation yields the recursion formula for step <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>, as required
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>s</i><su=
b><i>k</i></sub> <i>a</i> + <i>t</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> <i>b</i> =3D (<i>s<=
/i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub><i>s<=
/i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>) <i>a</i> + (<i>t</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=
=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub><i>t</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=
=921</sub>) <i>b</i></span>.</dd></dl>
