nverse</a> of the matrix <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Koshy_2002_63-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Koshy_2002-63"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Bach_1996_64-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Bach_1996-64"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant=
">determinant</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> equals <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=921)<sup><i>N</i>+1</sup></span>, since it equals =
the product of the determinants of the quotient matrices, each of which is =
negative one. Since the determinant of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></sp=
an> is never zero, the vector of the final remainders can be solved using t=
he inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span>
</p>
