<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =3D (=E2=88=921)<sup><i>N</i>+1</s=
up> ( <i>m</i><sub>22</sub> <i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>m</i><sub>12</sub> <i>b</=
i>)</span>,</dd></dl>
<p>the two integers of B=C3=A9zout's identity are <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>s</i> =3D (=E2=88=921)<sup><i>N</i>+1</sup><i>m</i><sub>22</sub></span> a=
nd <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i> =3D (=E2=88=921)<sup><i>N</i></sup><i>m=
</i><sub>12</sub></span>. The matrix method is as efficient as the equivale=
nt recursion, with two multiplications and two additions per step of the Eu=
clidean algorithm.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Euclid's_lemma_and_unique_f=
actorization"><span id=3D"Euclid.27s_lemma_and_unique_factorization"></span=
>Euclid's lemma and unique factorization</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Euclid's lemma and unique factorization"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>B=C3=A9zout's identity is essential to many applications of Euclid's alg=
orithm, such as demonstrating the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmet=
ic">unique factorization</a> of numbers into prime factors.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid=
ean_algorithm#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To illustrate this, suppose that a =
number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i></span> can be written as a product =
of two factors <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i></span> and <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>v</i></span>, that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i> =3D <i>u=
v</i></span>. If another number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></span> als=
o divides <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i></span> but is coprime with <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i></span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></=
span> must divide <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i></span>, by the following=
 argument: If the greatest common divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</=
i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></span> is <span class=3D"tex=
html">1</span>, then integers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> can be found such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">1 =3D <i>su</i> + <i>tw</i></span></dd></dl=
>
<p>by B=C3=A9zout's identity. Multiplying both sides by <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>v</i></span> gives the relation:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v</i> =3D <i>suv</i> + <i>twv</i> =3D <i=
>sL</i> + <i>twv</i></span></dd></dl>
<p>Since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></span> divides both terms on the =
right-hand side, it must also divide the left-hand side, <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>v</i></span>. This result is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_lemma" title=3D"Euclid's lemma">Euclid's lemma</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ore,_p._44_66-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Ore,_p._44-66"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Specifically, if a prime number divides <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</=
i></span>, then it must divide at least one factor of <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>L</i></span>. Conversely, if a number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i=
></span> is coprime to each of a series of numbers <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>a</i><sub>1</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>2</sub></=
span>, ..., <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span>, the=
n <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></span> is also coprime to their product,=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> =C3=97 <i>a</i><sub>2</sub> =
=C3=97 ... =C3=97 <i>a</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Or=
e,_p._44_66-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Ore,_p._44-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Euclid's lemma suffices to prove that every number has a unique fact=
orization into prime numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-67"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> To see this, assume the contrary, that there are two independent =
factorizations of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i></span> into <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> pr=
ime factors, respectively
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i> =3D <i>p</i><sub>1</sub><i>p</i><s=
ub>2</sub>...<i>p</i><sub><i>m</i></sub> =3D <i>q</i><sub>1</sub><i>q</i><s=
ub>2</sub>...<i>q</i><sub><i>n</i></sub>&nbsp;</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Since each prime <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> divides <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i></span> by assumption, it must also divide one of =
the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i></span> factors; since each <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i></span> is prime as well, it must be that <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i> =3D <i>q</i></span>. Iteratively dividing by the <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> factors shows that each <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>p</i></span> has an equal counterpart <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>q</i></span>; the two prime factorizations are identical except for their=
 order. The unique factorization of numbers into primes has many applicatio=
ns in mathematical proofs, as shown below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Linear_Diophantine_equation=
s">Linear Diophantine equations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Linear Diophantine equations"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Diophante_Bezout.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img alt=3D"&quot;A diagonal line running from the upper left corner=
 to the lower right. Fifteen circles are spaced at regular intervals along =
the line. Perpendicular x-y coordinate axes have their origin in the lower =
left corner; the line crossed the y-axis at the upper left and crosse the x=
-axis at the lower right.&quot;" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe=
dia/commons/thumb/9/94/Diophante_Bezout.svg/250px-Diophante_Bezout.svg.png"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"211" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"1786" data-file-height=3D"1506"></a><figcaption>Plot of =
a linear <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equation" tit=
le=3D"Diophantine equation">Diophantine equation</a>, <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">9<i>x</i> + 12<i>y</i> =3D 483</span>. The solutions are shown as blue c=
ircles.</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equation" title=3D"=
Diophantine equation">Diophantine equations</a> are equations in which the =
solutions are restricted to integers; they are named after the 3rd-century =
Alexandrian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophant=
us" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophantus</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> A typical <i>linear</i> Diophantine equation seeks int=
egers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>y</i></span> such that<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-69"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> + <i>by</i> =3D <i>c</i></span></=
dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>b</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i></span> are given intege=
rs. This can be written as an equation for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i>=
</span> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" tit=
le=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular arithmetic</a>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>c</i> mod <i>b</i></=
span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span> be the greatest common divis=
or of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>b</i></span>. Both terms in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> + <i>by</i>=
</span> are divisible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>; therefore=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i></span> must also be divisible by <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></span>, or the equation has no solutions. By divi=
ding both sides by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i>/<i>g</i></span>, the eq=
uation can be reduced to Bezout's identity
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>sa</i> + <i>tb</i> =3D <i>g</i></span>,<=
/dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>t</i></span> can be found by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm" title=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">ex=
tended Euclidean algorithm</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-70">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> This provides one solution to the Diophantine equation, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sub>1</sub> =3D <i>s</i> (<i>c</i>/<i>g</i>)</spa=
n> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i><sub>1</sub> =3D <i>t</i> (<i>c</i>/=
<i>g</i>)</span>.
</p><p>In general, a linear Diophantine equation has no solutions, or an in=
finite number of solutions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-71"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> To find the latter, consider two solutions, <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>(<i>x</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>y</i><sub>1</sub>)</span> and <span class=3D"tex=
html">(<i>x</i><sub>2</sub>, <i>y</i><sub>2</sub>)</span>, where
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>by</i><sub>1</su=
b> =3D <i>c</i> =3D <i>ax</i><sub>2</sub> + <i>by</i><sub>2</sub></span></d=
d></dl>
<p>or equivalently
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>(<i>x</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>=
x</i><sub>2</sub>) =3D <i>b</i>(<i>y</i><sub>2</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>y</i><sub=
>1</sub>)</span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, the smallest difference between two <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>x</i></span> solutions is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>/<i>g</i></span=
>, whereas the smallest difference between two <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y=
</i></span> solutions is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>/<i>g</i></span>. =
Thus, the solutions may be expressed as
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>x</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=88=92=
 <i>bu</i>/<i>g</i></span></dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>y</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>au</i>/<=
i>g</i></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>By allowing <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i></span> to vary over all pos=
sible integers, an infinite family of solutions can be generated from a sin=
gle solution <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>x</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>y</i><sub>1<=
/sub>)</span>. If the solutions are required to be <i>positive</i> integers=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>x</i> &gt; 0, <i>y</i> &gt; 0)</span>, only a =
finite number of solutions may be possible. This restriction on the accepta=
ble solutions allows some systems of Diophantine equations with more unknow=
ns than equations to have a finite number of solutions;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_=
algorithm#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> this is impossible for a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of =
linear equations">system of linear equations</a> when the solutions can be =
any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real num=
ber">real number</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underdet=
ermined_system" title=3D"Underdetermined system">Underdetermined system</a>=
).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multiplicative_inverses_and=
_the_RSA_algorithm">Multiplicative inverses and the RSA algorithm</h3><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Multiplicative in=
verses and the RSA algorithm"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_field" title=3D"Finite=
 field">finite field</a> is a set of numbers with four generalized operatio=
ns. The operations are called addition, subtraction, multiplication and div=
ision and have their usual properties, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Commutativity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Commutativity">c=
ommutativity</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associativity" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Associativity">associativity</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distributivity" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Distributivity">distributivity</a>. An example of a finite field is t=
he set of 13 numbers <span class=3D"texhtml">{0,&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2,&nbsp;...,&=
nbsp;12}</span> using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arit=
hmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular arithmetic</a>. In this field,=
 the results of any mathematical operation (addition, subtraction, multipli=
cation, or division) is reduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
dulo_operation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Modulo operation">modulo</a>=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">13</span>; that is, multiples of <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">13</span> are added or subtracted until the result is brought within=
 the range <span class=3D"texhtml">0</span>=E2=80=93<span class=3D"texhtml"=
>12</span>. For example, the result of <span class=3D"texhtml">5 =C3=97 7 =
=3D 35 mod 13 =3D 9</span>. Such finite fields can be defined for any prime=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span>; using more sophisticated definiti=
ons, they can also be defined for any power <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i=
></span> of a prime <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><sup><i>m</i></sup></sp=
an>. Finite fields are often called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/%C3%89variste_Galois" title=3D"=C3=89variste Galois">Galois</a> fields, a=
nd are abbreviated as <span class=3D"texhtml">GF(<i>p</i>)</span> or <span =
class=3D"texhtml">GF(<i>p</i><sup><i>m</i></sup></span>).
</p><p>In such a field with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> numbers=
, every nonzero element <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> has a uniqu=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse" =
title=3D"Modular multiplicative inverse">modular multiplicative inverse</a>=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> such that <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>aa</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> =3D <i>a</i><sup>=E2=
=88=921</sup><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 1 mod <i>m</i></span>. This inverse can be =
found by solving the congruence equation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> =
=E2=89=A1 1 mod <i>m</i></span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-73"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> or the equivalent linear Diophantine equation<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclide=
an_algorithm#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> + <i>my</i> =3D 1</span>.</dd></d=
l>
<p>This equation can be solved by the Euclidean algorithm, as described <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#Linear_Diophantin=
e_equations">above</a>. Finding multiplicative inverses is an essential ste=
p in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_algorithm" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"RSA algorithm">RSA algorithm</a>, which is widely used=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_commerce" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Electronic commerce">electronic commerce</a>; specifi=
cally, the equation determines the integer used to decrypt the message.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Although the RSA algori=
thm uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a> rather than fields, the Euclidean algorit=
hm can still be used to find a multiplicative inverse where one exists. The=
 Euclidean algorithm also has other applications in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Error-correcting_code" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Err=
or-correcting code">error-correcting codes</a>; for example, it can be used=
 as an alternative to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlekam=
p%E2%80%93Massey_algorithm" title=3D"Berlekamp=E2=80=93Massey algorithm">Be=
rlekamp=E2=80=93Massey algorithm</a> for decoding <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/BCH_code" title=3D"BCH code">BCH</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reed%E2%80%93Solomon_code" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Reed=E2=80=93Solomon code">Reed=E2=80=93Solomon codes</a>, which are =
based on Galois fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-76"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Chinese_remainder_theorem">=
Chinese remainder theorem</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: Chinese remainder theorem"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Euclid's algorithm can also be used to solve multiple linear Diophantine=
 equations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such equ=
ations arise in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remain=
der_theorem" title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese remainder theorem<=
/a>, which describes a novel method to represent an integer <i>x</i>. Inste=
ad of representing an integer by its digits, it may be represented by its r=
emainders <i>x</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> modulo a set of <i>N</i> coprime numb=
ers <i>m</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-78"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
