        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x\equiv (x_{1=
}M_{1}h_{1}+x_{2}M_{2}h_{2}+\cdots +x_{N}M_{N}h_{N}){\pmod {M}}\,.}</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8fed369909ea8053d7168a70800c32bcc5e21b24" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:56.81ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x\e=
quiv (x_{1}M_{1}h_{1}+x_{2}M_{2}h_{2}+\cdots +x_{N}M_{N}h_{N}){\pmod {M}}\,=
.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Since these numbers <i>h</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> are the multiplicative i=
nverses of the <i>M</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>, they may be found using Euclid'=
s algorithm as described in the previous subsection.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stern=E2=80=93Brocot_tree">=
<span id=3D"Stern.E2.80.93Brocot_tree"></span>Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree</h3=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</s=
pan><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algor=
ithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Stern=E2=80=
=93Brocot tree"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stern%E2%80%93Brocot=
_tree" title=3D"Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree">Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree</a></d=
iv>
<p>The Euclidean algorithm can be used to arrange the set of all positive <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D"Rational =
number">rational numbers</a> into an infinite <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_search_tree" title=3D"Binary search tree">binary search =
tree</a>, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stern%E2%80%9=
3Brocot_tree" title=3D"Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree">Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree=
</a>.
The number 1 (expressed as a fraction 1/1) is placed at the root of the tre=
e, and the location of any other number <i>a</i>/<i>b</i> can be found by c=
omputing gcd(<i>a</i>,<i>b</i>) using the original form of the Euclidean al=
gorithm, in which each step replaces the larger of the two given numbers by=
 its difference with the smaller number (not its remainder), stopping when =
two equal numbers are reached. A step of the Euclidean algorithm that repla=
ces the first of the two numbers corresponds to a step in the tree from a n=
ode to its right child, and a step that replaces the second of the two numb=
ers corresponds to a step in the tree from a node to its left child. The se=
quence of steps constructed in this way does not depend on whether <i>a</i>=
/<i>b</i> is given in lowest terms, and forms a path from the root to a nod=
e containing the number <i>a</i>/<i>b</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cit=
e_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> This fact can be used to prove that each positive ra=
tional number appears exactly once in this tree.
</p><p>For example, 3/4 can be found by starting at the root, going to the =
left once, then to the right twice:
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:SternBrocotTree.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://=
upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/SternBrocotTree.svg/500px=
-SternBrocotTree.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"240" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=3D"300"><=
/a><figcaption>The Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree, and the Stern=E2=80=93Brocot =
sequences of order <i>i</i> for <i>i</i> =3D 1, 2, 3, 4</figcaption></figur=
e>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}&amp;\gcd(3,4)&amp;\leftarrow \\=3D{}&amp;\gcd(3,1)&amp;\=
rightarrow \\=3D{}&amp;\gcd(2,1)&amp;\rightarrow \\=3D{}&amp;\gcd(1,1).\end=
{aligned}}}">
