<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Factorization_algorithms">F=
actorization algorithms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=
=3D"Edit section: Factorization algorithms"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Calculating a greatest common divisor is an essential step in several <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Inte=
ger factorization">integer factorization</a> algorithms,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean=
_algorithm#cite_note-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Pollard%27s_rho_algorithm" title=3D"Pollard's rho algorithm">Pol=
lard's rho algorithm</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-82"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shor%27s_algorithm" title=3D=
"Shor's algorithm">Shor's algorithm</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dixon%27s_fac=
torization_method" title=3D"Dixon's factorization method">Dixon's factoriza=
tion method</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lenstra_elliptic_curve_factori=
zation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lenstra elliptic curve factorization=
">Lenstra elliptic curve factorization</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#ci=
te_note-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The Euclidean algorithm may be used to find this GC=
D efficiently. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continued_fraction_=
factorization" title=3D"Continued fraction factorization">Continued fractio=
n factorization</a> uses continued fractions, which are determined using Eu=
clid's algorithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-86"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Algorithmic_efficiency">Alg=
orithmic efficiency</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Algorithmic efficiency"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Euclidean_Algorithm_Running_Time.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"&quot;A set of colored lines radiating=
 outwards from the origin of an x-y coordinate system. Each line correspond=
s to a set of number pairs requiring the same number of steps in the Euclid=
ean algorithm.&quot;" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/8/85/Euclidean_Algorithm_Running_Time.svg/250px-Euclidean_Algorithm_=
Running_Time.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"194" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"446" data-file-height=3D"346"></a><=
figcaption>Number of steps in the Euclidean algorithm for gcd(<i>x</i>,<i>y=
</i>). Lighter (red and yellow) points indicate relatively few steps, where=
as darker (violet and blue) points indicate more steps. The largest dark ar=
ea follows the line <i>y</i> =3D <i>=CE=A6x</i>, where <i>=CE=A6</i> is the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden rat=
io">golden ratio</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The computational efficiency of Euclid's algorithm has been studied thor=
oughly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This efficie=
ncy can be described by the number of division steps the algorithm requires=
, multiplied by the computational expense of each step. The first known ana=
lysis of Euclid's algorithm is due to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Antoine_Andr%C3%A9_Louis_Reynaud" title=3D"Antoine Andr=C3=A9 Louis Rey=
naud">A. A. L. Reynaud</a> in 1811,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-=
88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> who showed that the number of division steps on input (<i>u=
</i>, <i>v</i>) is bounded by <i>v</i>; later he improved this to <i>v</i>/=
2&nbsp;+&nbsp;2. Later, in 1841, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ierre_Joseph_%C3%89tienne_Finck" title=3D"Pierre Joseph =C3=89tienne Finck"=
>P. J. E. Finck</a> showed<sup id=3D"cite_ref-89" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-89"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> that the number of division steps is at most 2&nbsp;log<sub>2</sub>&=
nbsp;<i>v</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;1, and hence Euclid's algorithm runs in time poly=
nomial in the size of the input.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEShallit1994_90-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_a=
lgorithm#cite_note-FOOTNOTEShallit1994-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89mile_L%C3%A9ger" title=3D"=C3=89mile L=C3=A9ger"=
>=C3=89mile L=C3=A9ger</a>, in 1837, studied the worst case, which is when =
the inputs are consecutive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonac=
ci_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibonacci numbers">Fibonacci num=
bers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEShallit1994_90-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-FOOT=
NOTEShallit1994-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Finck's analysis was refined by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel_Lam%C3%A9" title=3D"Gabriel Lam=C3=A9=
">Gabriel Lam=C3=A9</a> in 1844,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-91"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> who showed that the number of steps required for completion is=
 never more than five times the number <i>h</i> of base-10 digits of the sm=
aller number&nbsp;<i>b</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-92"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_cost_model" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform cost model">uniform cost model</a> (=
suitable for analyzing the complexity of gcd calculation on numbers that fi=
t into a single machine word), each step of the algorithm takes <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constant_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Constant time">constant time</a>, and Lam=C3=A9's analysis implies that th=
e total running time is also <i>O</i>(<i>h</i>). However, in a model of com=
putation suitable for computation with larger numbers, the computational ex=
pense of a single remainder computation in the algorithm can be as large as=
 <i>O</i>(<i>h</i><sup>2</sup>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth-257-261_94-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorit=
hm#cite_note-Knuth-257-261-94"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In this case the total time for =
all of the steps of the algorithm can be analyzed using a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telescoping_series" title=3D"Telescoping series">te=
lescoping series</a>, showing that it is also <i>O</i>(<i>h</i><sup>2</sup>=
). Modern algorithmic techniques based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sch%C3%B6nhage%E2%80%93Strassen_algorithm" title=3D"Sch=C3=B6nh=
age=E2=80=93Strassen algorithm">Sch=C3=B6nhage=E2=80=93Strassen algorithm</=
a> for fast integer multiplication can be used to speed this up, leading to=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasilinear_time" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Quasilinear time">quasilinear algorithms</a> for the GCD.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Crandall_2001_95-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Crandall_2001-95"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Moller08_96-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Moller08-96"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Number_of_steps">Number of =
steps</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclid=
ean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Nu=
mber of steps"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>The number of steps to calculate the GCD of two natural numbers, <i>a</i=
> and <i>b</i>, may be denoted by <i>T</i>(<i>a</i>,&nbsp;<i>b</i>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._344_97-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._344-97"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> If <i>g</i> is the GCD of <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>, then <i>a</i>&nbsp;=3D=
&nbsp;<i>mg</i> and <i>b</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>ng</i> for two coprime number=
s <i>m</i> and <i>n</i>. Then
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) =3D <i>T</i>(<=
i>m</i>, <i>n</i>)</span></dd></dl>
<p>as may be seen by dividing all the steps in the Euclidean algorithm by <=
i>g</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-98" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the same=
 argument, the number of steps remains the same if <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> ar=
e multiplied by a common factor <i>w</i>: <i>T</i>(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) =3D =
<i>T</i>(<i>wa</i>, <i>wb</i>). Therefore, the number of steps <i>T</i> may=
 vary dramatically between neighboring pairs of numbers, such as T(<i>a</i>=
, <i>b</i>) and T(<i>a</i>,&nbsp;<i>b</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;1), depending on the =
size of the two GCDs.
</p><p>The recursive nature of the Euclidean algorithm gives another equati=
on
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>) =3D 1 + <i>T</=
i>(<i>b</i>, <i>r</i><sub>0</sub>) =3D 2 + <i>T</i>(<i>r</i><sub>0</sub>, <=
i>r</i><sub>1</sub>) =3D =E2=80=A6 =3D <i>N</i> + <i>T</i>(<i>r</i><sub><i>=
N</i>=E2=88=922</sub>, <i>r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub>) =3D <i>N</i> =
+ 1</span></dd></dl>
<p>where <i>T</i>(<i>x</i>, 0)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0 by assumption.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Knuth,_p._344_97-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._344-97"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Worst-case">Worst-case</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algori=
thm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Worst-case">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>If the Euclidean algorithm requires <i>N</i> steps for a pair of natural=
 numbers <i>a</i>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<i>b</i>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;0, the smallest va=
lues of <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> for which this is true are the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Fibonacci number">Fibonacci numbers</a> <i>F</i><sub><i>N</i>+2</sub> and =
<i>F</i><sub><i>N</i>+1</sub>, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._3=
43_99-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
dean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._343-99"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More precisely, if t=
he Euclidean algorithm requires <i>N</i> steps for the pair <i>a</i>&nbsp;&=
gt;&nbsp;<i>b</i>, then one has <i>a</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><=
i>N</i>+2</sub> and <i>b</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><i>N</i>+1</s=
ub>. This can be shown by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemat=
ical_induction" title=3D"Mathematical induction">induction</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-100" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If <i>N</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;1, =
<i>b</i> divides <i>a</i> with no remainder; the smallest natural numbers f=
or which this is true is <i>b</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;1 and <i>a</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbs=
p;2, which are <i>F</i><sub>2</sub> and <i>F</i><sub>3</sub>, respectively.=
 Now assume that the result holds for all values of <i>N</i> up to <i>M</i>=
&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1. The first step of the <i>M</i>-step algorithm is <i=
>a</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>q</i><sub>0</sub><i>b</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;<i>r</i><sub>=
0</sub>, and the Euclidean algorithm requires <i>M</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;=
1 steps for the pair <i>b</i>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<i>r</i><sub>0</sub>. By induc=
tion hypothesis, one has <i>b</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><i>M</i>=
+1</sub> and <i>r</i><sub>0</sub>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><i>M</i>=
</sub>. Therefore, <i>a</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>q</i><sub>0</sub><i>b</i>&nbsp=
;+&nbsp;<i>r</i><sub>0</sub>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>b</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;<i>r<=
/i><sub>0</sub>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><i>M</i>+1</sub>&nbsp;+&nb=
sp;<i>F</i><sub><i>M</i></sub>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>F</i><sub><i>M</i>+2</sub>,
which is the desired inequality.
This proof, published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel_L=
am%C3%A9" title=3D"Gabriel Lam=C3=A9">Gabriel Lam=C3=A9</a> in 1844, repres=
ents the beginning of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computationa=
l_complexity_theory" title=3D"Computational complexity theory">computationa=
l complexity theory</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-101"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> and also the first practical application of the Fibonacci numbers.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._343_99-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._343-99"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>This result suffices to show that the number of steps in Euclid's al=
gorithm can never be more than five times the number of its digits (base 10=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-102" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For if the alg=
orithm requires <i>N</i> steps, then <i>b</i> is greater than or equal to <=
i>F</i><sub><i>N</i>+1</sub> which in turn is greater than or equal to <i>=
=CF=86</i><sup><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sup>, where <i>=CF=86</i> is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">gold=
en ratio</a>. Since <i>b</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;<i>=CF=86</i><sup><i>N</i>=
=E2=88=921</sup>, then <i>N</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1&nbsp;=E2=89=A4&nbsp;l=
og<sub><i>=CF=86</i></sub><i>b</i>. Since log<sub>10</sub><i>=CF=86</i>&nbs=
p;&gt;&nbsp;1/5, (<i>N</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1)/5&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;log<sub>=
10</sub><i>=CF=86</i>&nbsp;log<sub><i>=CF=86</i></sub><i>b</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbs=
p;log<sub>10</sub><i>b</i>. Thus, <i>N</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A4&nbsp;5&nbsp;log<s=
ub>10</sub><i>b</i>. Thus, the Euclidean algorithm always needs less than <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation" title=3D"Big O nota=
tion"><i>O</i>(<i>h</i>)</a> divisions, where <i>h</i> is the number of dig=
its in the smaller number <i>b</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Average">Average</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Average"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The average number of steps taken by the Euclidean algorithm has been de=
fined in three different ways. The first definition is the average time <i>=
T</i>(<i>a</i>) required to calculate the GCD of a given number <i>a</i> an=
d a smaller natural number <i>b</i> chosen with equal probability from the =
integers 0 to <i>a</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth,_p._3=
44_97-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
dean_algorithm#cite_note-Knuth,_p._344-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e T(a)=3D{\frac {1}{a}}\sum _{0\leq b&lt;a}T(a,b).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>T</mi>
