<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_expense_per_s=
tep">Computational expense per step</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Computational expense per step"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In each step <i>k</i> of the Euclidean algorithm, the quotient <i>q</i><=
sub><i>k</i></sub> and remainder <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> are computed f=
or a given pair of integers <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> and <i>r<=
/i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <=
i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i>r</i>=
<sub><i>k</i></sub>.</span></dd></dl>
<p>The computational expense per step is associated chiefly with finding <i=
>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>, since the remainder <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =
can be calculated quickly from <i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub>, <i>r<=
/i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>, and <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> =3D <i>r</i><su=
b><i>k</i>=E2=88=922</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> <i>r</i><s=
ub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>.</span></dd></dl>
<p>The computational expense of dividing <i>h</i>-bit numbers scales as <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>O</i>(<i>h</i>(<i>=E2=84=93</i> + 1))</span>, where=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=E2=84=93</span>=
 is the length of the quotient.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Knuth-257-261_94-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorith=
m#cite_note-Knuth-257-261-94"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For comparison, Euclid's original subtraction-based algorithm can be=
 much slower. A single integer division is equivalent to the quotient <i>q<=
/i> number of subtractions. If the ratio of <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> is very l=
arge, the quotient is large and many subtractions will be required. On the =
other hand, it has been shown that the quotients are very likely to be smal=
l integers. The probability of a given quotient <i>q</i> is approximately <=
span class=3D"texhtml">ln |<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1=
em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>u</i>/(<i>u</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span>|</span> wh=
ere <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i> =3D (<i>q</i> + 1)<sup>2</sup></span>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For illustration=
, the probability of a quotient of 1, 2, 3, or 4 is roughly 41.5%, 17.0%, 9=
.3%, and 5.9%, respectively. Since the operation of subtraction is faster t=
han division, particularly for large numbers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-116" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm=
#cite_note-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the subtraction-based Euclid's algorithm is co=
mpetitive with the division-based version.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-117" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#ci=
te_note-117"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> This is exploited in the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Binary_GCD_algorithm" title=3D"Binary GCD algorithm">binar=
y version</a> of Euclid's algorithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-118" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_not=
e-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Combining the estimated number of steps with the estimated computati=
onal expense per step shows that the Euclid's algorithm grows quadratically=
 (<i>h</i><sup>2</sup>) with the average number of digits <i>h</i> in the i=
nitial two numbers <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>. Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h<=
/i><sub>0</sub>, <i>h</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>h</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921=
</sub></span> represent the number of digits in the successive remainders <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>, <i>r</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>=
r</i><sub><i>N</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>. Since the number of steps <i>N</=
i> grows linearly with <i>h</i>, the running time is bounded by
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
