<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alternative_methods">Altern=
ative methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Alternative methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Euclid's algorithm is widely used in practice, especially for small numb=
ers, due to its simplicity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-119"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> For comparison, the efficiency of alternatives to Euclid's algor=
ithm may be determined.
</p><p>One inefficient approach to finding the GCD of two natural numbers <=
i>a</i> and <i>b</i> is to calculate all their common divisors; the GCD is =
then the largest common divisor. The common divisors can be found by dividi=
ng both numbers by successive integers from 2 to the smaller number <i>b</i=
>. The number of steps of this approach grows linearly with <i>b</i>, or ex=
ponentially in the number of digits. Another inefficient approach is to fin=
d the prime factors of one or both numbers. As noted <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#Greatest_common_divisor">above</a>, =
the GCD equals the product of the prime factors shared by the two numbers <=
i>a</i> and <i>b</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schroeder_21_9-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-=
Schroeder_21-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Present methods for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Integer factorization">prime f=
actorization</a> are also inefficient; many modern cryptography systems eve=
n rely on that inefficiency.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schroeder_216_12-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm=
#cite_note-Schroeder_216-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_GCD_algorithm" t=
itle=3D"Binary GCD algorithm">binary GCD algorithm</a> is an efficient alte=
rnative that substitutes division with faster operations by exploiting the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Binary numeral system">binary</a> representation used b=
y computers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-120" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-120"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>119<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-121"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, this alterna=
tive also scales like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big-O_notati=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Big-O notation"><i>O</i>(<i>h</i>=C2=B2)=
</a>. It is generally faster than the Euclidean algorithm on real computers=
, even though it scales in the same way.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Crandall_2001_9=
5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean=
_algorithm#cite_note-Crandall_2001-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Additional efficiency ca=
n be gleaned by examining only the leading digits of the two numbers <i>a</=
i> and <i>b</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-122" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-122"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-123" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The binary algo=
rithm can be extended to other bases (<i>k</i>-ary algorithms),<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_algorithm#cite_note-124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> with up to fivefold increase=
s in speed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-125"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lehmer%27s_GCD_algorithm" title=3D"Lehm=
er's GCD algorithm">Lehmer's GCD algorithm</a> uses the same general princi=
ple as the binary algorithm to speed up GCD computations in arbitrary bases=
.
</p><p>A recursive approach for very large integers (with more than 25,000 =
digits) leads to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasilinear_time"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quasilinear time">quasilinear</a> integer G=
CD algorithms,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-126" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-126"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> su=
ch as those of Sch=C3=B6nhage,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-127" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-127"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-128" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-128"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
 Stehl=C3=A9 and Zimmermann.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-129" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-129"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> These algorithms exploit the 2=C3=972 matrix form of the Euclid=
ean algorithm given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algo=
rithm#Matrix_method">above</a>. These quasilinear methods generally scale a=
s <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>O</i>(<i>h</i> log <i>h</i><sup>2</sup> log lo=
g <i>h</i>).</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Crandall_2001_95-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-=
Crandall_2001-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Moller08_96-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-Moller08-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclid=
ean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Ge=
neralizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Although the Euclidean algorithm is used to find the greatest common div=
isor of two natural numbers (positive integers), it may be generalized to t=
he real numbers, and to other mathematical objects, such as <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>,=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lang_1984_130-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Lang_1984-130"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_integer" title=3D"=
Quadratic integer">quadratic integers</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-weinberger_131=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_=
algorithm#cite_note-weinberger-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurwitz_quaternion" title=3D"Hurwitz quaternion">Hurwitz=
 quaternions</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stillwell151-152_132-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_not=
e-stillwell151-152-132"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the latter cases, the Euclidean alg=
orithm is used to demonstrate the crucial property of unique factorization,=
 i.e., that such numbers can be factored uniquely into <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_element" title=3D"Irreducible element">irr=
educible elements</a>, the counterparts of prime numbers. Unique factorizat=
ion is essential to many proofs of number theory.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rational_and_real_numbers">=
Rational and real numbers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=
=3D"Edit section: Rational and real numbers"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Euclid's algorithm can be applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>, as described by =
Euclid in Book 10 of his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid=
%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i>. The goal of th=
e algorithm is to identify a real number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> such that two given real numbers, <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, are integer multip=
les of it: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>mg</i></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D <i>ng</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-We=
il_1983_29-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Weil_1983-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This identification=
 is equivalent to finding an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integ=
er_relation_algorithm" title=3D"Integer relation algorithm">integer relatio=
n</a> among the real numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">b</span>; that is, it determines integers <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">t</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
sa</i> + <i>tb</i> =3D 0</span>. If such an equation is possible, <i>a</i> =
and <i>b</i> are called commensurable lengths, otherwise they are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commensurability_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Commensurability (mathematics)">incommensurable lengths</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-133" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
idean_algorithm#cite_note-133"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>132<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-134" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm=
#cite_note-134"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>133<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The real-number Euclidean algorithm differs from its integer counter=
part in two respects. First, the remainders <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i=
><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> are real numbers, although the quotients <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> are integers as before=
. Second, the algorithm is not guaranteed to end in a finite number <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> of steps. If it=
 does, the fraction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>/<i>b</i></span> is a r=
ational number, i.e., the ratio of two integers
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
