er/svg/ebe70bc1e1fa440faa4c9029ff65f0947ae83e64" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:15.779ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
frac {a}{b}}=3D{\frac {mg}{ng}}=3D{\frac {m}{n}},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>and can be written as a finite continued fraction <span class=3D"texhtml=
">[<i>q</i><sub>0</sub>; <i>q</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>q</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <=
i>q</i><sub><i>N</i></sub>]</span>. If the algorithm does not stop, the fra=
ction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>/<i>b</i></span> is an <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number" title=3D"Irrational number">i=
rrational number</a> and can be described by an infinite continued fraction=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">[<i>q</i><sub>0</sub>; <i>q</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>q<=
/i><sub>2</sub>, =E2=80=A6]</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-135" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note=
-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>134<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Examples of infinite continued fractions are the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">gold=
en ratio</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i> =3D [1; 1, 1, ...]</span=
> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root_of_2" title=
=3D"Square root of 2">square root of two</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><span=
 class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0=
.1em;">2</span></span> =3D [1; 2, 2, ...]</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-136" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algor=
ithm#cite_note-136"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>135<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When applied to two arbitrary real numbers=
, the algorithm is unlikely to stop, since <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Almost_all" title=3D"Almost all">almost all</a> ratios <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>/<i>b</i></span> of two real numbers are irrational.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-137" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-137"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An infinite continued fraction may be truncated at a step <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> [<i>q</i><sub>0</sub>; <i>q</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>q</i=
><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>]</span> to yield an approxi=
mation to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>/<i>b</i></span> that improves as=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is incr=
eased. The approximation is described by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Convergent_(continued_fraction)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Conv=
ergent (continued fraction)">convergents</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</=
i><sub><i>k</i></sub>/<i>n</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>; the numerator and=
 denominators are coprime and obey the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Recurrence_relation" title=3D"Recurrence relation">recurrence relation=
</a>
</p>
