<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_greatest_=
common_divisor" title=3D"Polynomial greatest common divisor">Polynomial gre=
atest common divisor</a></div>
<p>Polynomials in a single variable <i>x</i> can be added, multiplied and f=
actored into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_polynomia=
l" title=3D"Irreducible polynomial">irreducible polynomials</a>, which are =
the analogs of the prime numbers for integers. The greatest common divisor =
polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> of two polynom=
ials <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is defined as the product of their shared=
 irreducible polynomials, which can be identified using the Euclidean algor=
ithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lang_1984_130-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Lang_1984-130"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The basic procedure is similar to that for integers. At each ste=
p <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>, a quo=
tient polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>(<i>x</=
i>)</span> and a remainder polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>=
<i>k</i></sub>(<i>x</i>)</span> are identified to satisfy the recursive equ=
ation
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e r_{k-2}(x)=3Dq_{k}(x)r_{k-1}(x)+r_{k}(x),}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle r_{k-2}(x)=3D=
q_{k}(x)r_{k-1}(x)+r_{k}(x),}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9a124a8ba0c2bafb28022d39fda1b09864b696b1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:31.881ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r_=
{k-2}(x)=3Dq_{k}(x)r_{k-1}(x)+r_{k}(x),}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>=E2=88=922</sub>(<i>x</i>) =
=3D <i>a</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>=E2=
=88=921</sub>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>. Each quotient polyno=
mial is chosen such that each remainder is either zero or has a degree that=
 is smaller than the degree of its predecessor: <span class=3D"texhtml">deg=
[<i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>(<i>x</i>)] &lt; deg[<i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=
=88=921</sub>(<i>x</i>)]</span>. Since the degree is a nonnegative integer,=
 and since it decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm concludes =
in a finite number of steps. The last nonzero remainder is the greatest com=
mon divisor of the original two polynomials, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</=
i>(<i>x</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-139" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-139"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For example, consider the following two quartic polynomials, which e=
ach factor into two quadratic polynomials
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}a(x)&amp;=3Dx^{4}-4x^{3}+4x^{2}-3x+14=3D(x^{2}-5x+7)(x^{2=
}+x+2)\qquad {\text{and}}\\b(x)&amp;=3Dx^{4}+8x^{3}+12x^{2}+17x+6=3D(x^{2}+=
7x+3)(x^{2}+x+2).\end{aligned}}}">
