egin{aligned}a(x)&amp;=3Dx^{4}-4x^{3}+4x^{2}-3x+14=3D(x^{2}-5x+7)(x^{2}+x+2=
)\qquad {\text{and}}\\b(x)&amp;=3Dx^{4}+8x^{3}+12x^{2}+17x+6=3D(x^{2}+7x+3)=
(x^{2}+x+2).\end{aligned}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_long_division" title=
=3D"Polynomial long division">Dividing</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>=
(<i>x</i>)</span> by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> yiel=
ds a remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>(<i>x</i>) =3D <=
i>x</i><sup>3</sup> + (2/3)<i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + (5/3)<i>x</i> =E2=88=92 (=
2/3)</span>. In the next step, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</=
span> is divided by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>(<i>x</i>)<=
/span> yielding a remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub>(<i=
>x</i>) =3D <i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>x</i> + 2</span>. Finally, dividing <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>0</sub>(<i>x</i>)</span> by <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub>(<i>x</i>)</span> yields a zero remainder,=
 indicating that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>1</sub>(<i>x</i>)</sp=
an> is the greatest common divisor polynomial of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>a</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>(<i>x</i>)</spa=
n>, consistent with their factorization.
</p><p>Many of the applications described above for integers carry over to =
polynomials.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-140" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-140"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>139<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
Euclidean algorithm can be used to solve linear Diophantine equations and C=
hinese remainder problems for polynomials; continued fractions of polynomia=
ls can also be defined.
</p><p>The polynomial Euclidean algorithm has other applications, such as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sturm_chain" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Sturm chain">Sturm chains</a>, a method for counting the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_of_a_function" title=3D"Zero of a fu=
nction">zeros of a polynomial</a> that lie inside a given <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathemat=
ics)">real interval</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-141" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-141"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>140<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> This in turn has applications in several areas, such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Routh%E2%80%93Hurwitz_stability_criterion=
" title=3D"Routh=E2=80=93Hurwitz stability criterion">Routh=E2=80=93Hurwitz=
 stability criterion</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contro=
l_theory" title=3D"Control theory">control theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_=
algorithm#cite_note-142"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>141<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Finally, the coefficients of the polynomials need not be drawn from =
integers, real numbers or even the complex numbers. For example, the coeffi=
cients may be drawn from a general field, such as the finite fields <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">GF(<i>p</i>)</span> described above. The corresponding con=
clusions about the Euclidean algorithm and its applications hold even for s=
uch polynomials.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lang_1984_130-2" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Lang_1=
984-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Gaussian_integers">Gaussian=
 integers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEu=
clidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section=
: Gaussian integers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gaussian_primes.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img alt=3D"&quot;A set of dots lying within a circle. The pattern of=
 dots has fourfold symmetry, i.e., rotations by 90 degrees leave the patter=
n unchanged. The pattern can also be mirrored about four lines passing thro=
ugh the center of the circle: the vertical and horizontal axes, and the two=
 diagonal lines at =C2=B145 degrees.&quot;" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia=
.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Gaussian_primes.svg/250px-Gaussian_primes=
.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"440" data-file-height=3D"440"></a><figcaption>D=
istribution of Gaussian primes <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i> + <i>vi</i>=
</span> in the complex plane, with norms <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><s=
up>2</sup> + <i>v</i><sup>2</sup></span> less than 500</figcaption></figure=
>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integer" title=3D"=
Gaussian integer">Gaussian integers</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex numbers</a> of t=
he form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> =3D <i>u</i> + <i>vi</i></spa=
n>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span=
> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v</span> ar=
e ordinary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integ=
er">integers</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-143" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-143"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span>=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_unit" title=3D"I=
maginary unit">square root of negative one</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stillwel=
l_2003_144-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stillwell_2003-144"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By defining =
an analog of the Euclidean algorithm, Gaussian integers can be shown to be =
uniquely factorizable, by the argument <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#B%C3%A9zout's_identity">above</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Gauss_1832_44-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Gauss_1832-44"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This unique=
 factorization is helpful in many applications, such as deriving all <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_triple" title=3D"Pythagorean=
 triple">Pythagorean triples</a> or proving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_theorem_on_sums_of_two_squares" title=3D"Fermat's theo=
rem on sums of two squares">Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Stillwell_2003_144-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stillwell_2003-144">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> In general, the Euclidean algorithm is convenient in such appl=
ications, but not essential; for example, the theorems can often be proven =
by other arguments.
</p><p>The Euclidean algorithm developed for two Gaussian integers <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B1</span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B2</span> is nearly =
the same as that for ordinary integers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hensley_145-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algor=
ithm#cite_note-hensley-145"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>143<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but differs in two respects. As be=
fore, we set <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>=E2=88=922</sub> =3D <i>=
=CE=B1</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub>=E2=88=921</sub>=
 =3D <i>=CE=B2</i></span>, and the task at each step <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is to identify a quotient <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> and a remainder <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e r_{k}=3Dr_{k-2}-q_{k}r_{k-1},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <msub>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle r_{k}=3Dr_{k-=
2}-q_{k}r_{k-1},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4d869488f195aa53279b6ed587a3537815c4ed51" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:19.325ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r_=
{k}=3Dr_{k-2}-q_{k}r_{k-1},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where every remainder is strictly smaller than its predecessor: <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; paddin=
g-right:0.1em;"><i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>| &lt; |<span class=3D"no=
wrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>r</i><sub><i>k<=
/i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>|</span>. The first difference is that the quotie=
nts and remainders are themselves Gaussian integers, and thus are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">=
complex numbers</a>. The quotients <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub><i>=
k</i></sub></span> are generally found by rounding the real and complex par=
ts of the exact ratio (such as the complex number <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>=CE=B1</i>/<i>=CE=B2</i></span>) to the nearest integers.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-hensley_145-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-hensley-145"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>143<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The second dif=
ference lies in the necessity of defining how one complex remainder can be =
"smaller" than another. To do this, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Norm_(mathematics)" title=3D"Norm (mathematics)">norm function</a> <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>u</i> + <i>vi</i>) =3D <i>u</i><sup>2</sup>=
 + <i>v</i><sup>2</sup></span> is defined, which converts every Gaussian in=
teger <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i> + <i>vi</i></span> into an ordinary =
integer. After each step <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">k</span> of the Euclidean algorithm, the norm of the remainder <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>r</i><sub><i>k</i></sub>)</span> is smaller=
 than the norm of the preceding remainder, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=
(<i>r</i><sub><i>k</i>=E2=88=921</sub>)</span>. Since the norm is a nonnega=
tive integer and decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm for Gau=
ssian integers ends in a finite number of steps.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-146" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algori=
thm#cite_note-146"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The final nonzero remainder is <span class=
=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>=CE=B1</i>, <i>=CE=B2</i>)</span>, the Gaussian integer=
 of largest norm that divides both <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">=CE=B1</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">=CE=B2</span>; it is unique up to multiplication by a un=
it, <span class=3D"texhtml">=C2=B11</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">=C2=
=B1<i>i</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-147" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-147"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>145<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>Many of the other applications of the Euclidean algorithm carry over=
 to Gaussian integers. For example, it can be used to solve linear Diophant=
ine equations and Chinese remainder problems for Gaussian integers;<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-148" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-148"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>146<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> continued fractions of =
Gaussian integers can also be defined.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hensley_145-2" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algori=
thm#cite_note-hensley-145"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>143<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Euclidean_domains">Euclidea=
n domains</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEu=
clidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section=
: Euclidean domains"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A set of elements under two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bin=
ary_operation" title=3D"Binary operation">binary operations</a>, denoted as=
 addition and multiplication, is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Euclidean_domain" title=3D"Euclidean domain">Euclidean domain</a> i=
f it forms a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_ring" tit=
le=3D"Commutative ring">commutative ring</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> and, roughly speaking, if a generalize=
d Euclidean algorithm can be performed on them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorit=
hm#cite_note-149"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>147<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-150" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-150"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>148<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The two operations of such a ring need not be the addition an=
d multiplication of ordinary arithmetic; rather, they can be more general, =
such as the operations of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_=
(mathematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">mathematical group</a> or <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monoid" title=3D"Monoid">monoid</a>. N=
evertheless, these general operations should respect many of the laws gover=
ning ordinary arithmetic, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Commutative_property" title=3D"Commutative property">commutativity</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_property" title=3D"Associ=
ative property">associativity</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Distributive_property" title=3D"Distributive property">distributivity</=
a>.
</p><p>The generalized Euclidean algorithm requires a <i>Euclidean function=
</i>, i.e., a mapping <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">f</span> from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">R</span> into the set of nonnegative integers such that, for any two nonz=
ero elements <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>=
 in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>, the=
re exist <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">q</span>=
 and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> in =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> such tha=
t <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>qb</i> + <i>r</i></span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>r</i>) &lt; <i>f</i>(<i>b</i>)</span>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-151" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-151"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>149<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Examples of such mapp=
ings are the absolute value for integers, the degree for <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univariate_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Univariate polynomial">univariate polynomials</a>, and the norm for Gau=
ssian integers <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm=
#Gaussian_integers">above</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-152" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-152"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>150<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-153" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-153"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>151<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
 basic principle is that each step of the algorithm reduces <i>f</i> inexor=
ably; hence, if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f=
</span> can be reduced only a finite number of times, the algorithm must st=
op in a finite number of steps. This principle relies on the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Well-order" title=3D"Well-order">well-ordering</=
a> property of the non-negative integers, which asserts that every non-empt=
y set of non-negative integers has a smallest member.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sh=
arpe_154-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eu=
clidean_algorithm#cite_note-sharpe-154"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>152<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_=
arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmetic">fundamental theorem=
 of arithmetic</a> applies to any Euclidean domain: Any number from a Eucli=
dean domain can be factored uniquely into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Irreducible_element" title=3D"Irreducible element">irreducible elem=
ents</a>. Any Euclidean domain is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Unique_factorization_domain" title=3D"Unique factorization domain">unique=
 factorization domain</a> (UFD), although the converse is not true.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-sharpe_154-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-sharpe-154"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>152<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Euc=
lidean domains and the UFD's are subclasses of the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/GCD_domain" title=3D"GCD domain">GCD domains</a>, domains =
in which a greatest common divisor of two numbers always exists.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-155" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-155"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>153=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other words, a greatest =
common divisor may exist (for all pairs of elements in a domain), although =
it may not be possible to find it using a Euclidean algorithm. A Euclidean =
domain is always a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal=
_domain" title=3D"Principal ideal domain">principal ideal domain</a> (PID),=
 an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_domain" title=3D"Inte=
gral domain">integral domain</a> in which every <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theory)">ideal</a> =
is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal" title=3D"Pri=
ncipal ideal">principal ideal</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-156" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-=
156"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>154<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Again, the converse is not true: not every PID is a Eucli=
dean domain.
</p><p>The unique factorization of Euclidean domains is useful in many appl=
ications. For example, the unique factorization of the Gaussian integers is=
 convenient in deriving formulae for all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Pythagorean_triple" title=3D"Pythagorean triple">Pythagorean triples=
</a> and in proving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_the=
orem_on_sums_of_two_squares" title=3D"Fermat's theorem on sums of two squar=
es">Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stillwe=
ll_2003_144-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-Stillwell_2003-144"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Unique fact=
orization was also a key element in an attempted proof of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last The=
orem">Fermat's Last Theorem</a> published in 1847 by Gabriel Lam=C3=A9, the=
 same mathematician who analyzed the efficiency of Euclid's algorithm, base=
d on a suggestion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Liouvi=
lle" title=3D"Joseph Liouville">Joseph Liouville</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15=
7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_a=
lgorithm#cite_note-157"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>155<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Lam=C3=A9's approach required the uniq=
ue factorization of numbers of the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> + =
<i>=CF=89y</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">x</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">y</span> are integers, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=89</i> =
=3D <i>e</i><sup>2<i>i=CF=80</i>/<i>n</i></sup></span> is an <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>th root of 1, that is, =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=89</i><sup><i>n</i></sup> =3D 1</span>. Alth=
ough this approach succeeds for some values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> (such as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
n</i> =3D 3</span>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eisenstein=
_integer" title=3D"Eisenstein integer">Eisenstein integers</a>), in general=
 such numbers do <em>not</em> factor uniquely. This failure of unique facto=
rization in some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclotomic_field"=
 title=3D"Cyclotomic field">cyclotomic fields</a> led <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Kummer" title=3D"Ernst Kummer">Ernst Kummer</a> t=
o the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_number" tit=
le=3D"Ideal number">ideal numbers</a> and, later, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" title=3D"Richard Dedekind">Richard Dedeki=
nd</a> to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" tit=
le=3D"Ideal (ring theory)">ideals</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-158" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_n=
ote-158"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>156<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Unique_factorization_of_qua=
dratic_integers">Unique factorization of quadratic integers</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Unique factorization o=
f quadratic integers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Eisenstein_primes.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img alt=3D"&quot;A set of dots lying within a circle. The pattern =
of dots has sixfold symmetry, i.e., rotations by 60 degrees leave the patte=
rn unchanged. The pattern can also be mirrored about six lines passing thro=
ugh the center of the circle: the vertical and horizontal axes, and the fou=
r diagonal lines at =C2=B130 and =C2=B160 degrees.&quot;" src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Eisenstein_primes.svg/250px=
-Eisenstein_primes.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"247"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1203" data-file-height=3D"118=
8"></a><figcaption>Distribution of Eisenstein primes <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>u</i> + <i>v=CF=89</i></span> in the complex plane, with norms less th=
an 500. The number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">=CF=89</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_of_unity=
" title=3D"Root of unity">cube root of 1</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_integer" title=3D=
"Quadratic integer">quadratic integer</a> rings are helpful to illustrate E=
uclidean domains. Quadratic integers are generalizations of the Gaussian in=
tegers in which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_unit=
" title=3D"Imaginary unit">imaginary unit</a> <i>i</i> is replaced by a num=
ber <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=89</span>=
. Thus, they have the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i> + <i>v=CF=89</i=
></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u=
</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v</sp=
an> are integers and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">=CF=89</span> has one of two forms, depending on a parameter <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span>. If <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span> does not equal a multi=
ple of four plus one, then
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \omega =3D{\sqrt {D}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CF=89<!-- =CF=89 --></mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mi>D</mi>
          </msqrt>
