rac {1+{\sqrt {D}}}{2}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/cd3f1793eef655097a24765d6b48d950a45302ea" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:13.89ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \om=
ega =3D{\frac {1+{\sqrt {D}}}{2}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>If the function <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">f</span> corresponds to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_=
norm" title=3D"Field norm">norm</a> function, such as that used to order th=
e Gaussian integers <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algo=
rithm#Gaussian_integers">above</a>, then the domain is known as <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norm-Euclidean_field" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Norm-Euclidean field">norm-Euclidean</a></i>. The norm-Euclidea=
n rings of quadratic integers are exactly those where <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span> is one of the values =E2=88=
=9211, =E2=88=927, =E2=88=923, =E2=88=922, =E2=88=921, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 11, 1=
3, 17, 19, 21, 29, 33, 37, 41, 57, or 73.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-159" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cit=
e_note-159"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>157<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-160" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-160"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>158<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The cases <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> =3D =E2=88=921</span> an=
d <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> =3D =E2=88=923</span> yield the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integer" title=3D"Gaussian integ=
er">Gaussian integers</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eise=
nstein_integer" title=3D"Eisenstein integer">Eisenstein integers</a>, respe=
ctively.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span=
> is allowed to be any Euclidean function, then the list of possible values=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span> for =
which the domain is Euclidean is not yet known.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Clark_19=
94_161-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
idean_algorithm#cite_note-Clark_1994-161"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The first example of=
 a Euclidean domain that was not norm-Euclidean (with <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>D</i> =3D 69</span>) was published in 1994.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Clark_=
1994_161-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eu=
clidean_algorithm#cite_note-Clark_1994-161"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1973, Weinberge=
r proved that a quadratic integer ring with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i=
> &gt; 0</span> is Euclidean if, and only if, it is a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal_domain" title=3D"Principal ideal domain=
">principal ideal domain</a>, provided that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Generalized_Riemann_hypothesis" title=3D"Generalized Riemann =
hypothesis">generalized Riemann hypothesis</a> holds.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-we=
inberger_131-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-weinberger-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Noncommutative_rings">Nonco=
mmutative rings</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DEuclidean_algorithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Noncommutative rings"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Euclidean algorithm may be applied to some noncommutative rings such=
 as the set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurwitz_quaternion"=
 title=3D"Hurwitz quaternion">Hurwitz quaternions</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-s=
tillwell151-152_132-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-stillwell151-152-132"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-bgv_162-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-bgv-162"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>160<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Let <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B1</span> and <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B2</span> repres=
ent two elements from such a ring. They have a common right divisor <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B4</span> if <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> =3D <i>=CE=BE=CE=B4</i></span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B2</i> =3D <i>=CE=B7=CE=B4</i></span> for some choice=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BE</span>=
 and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B7</span=
> in the ring. Similarly, they have a common left divisor if <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> =3D <i>d=CE=BE</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>=CE=B2</i> =3D <i>d=CE=B7</i></span> for some choice of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BE</span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B7</span> in the ring. =
Since multiplication is not commutative, there are two versions of the Eucl=
idean algorithm, one for right divisors and one for left divisors.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-stillwell151-152_132-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-stillwell151-152-132">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-bgv_162-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-bgv-162"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>160<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Choosing the right divisors, the first step in finding the <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>=CE=B1</i>, <i>=CE=B2</i>)</span> by the Euclidean alg=
orithm can be written
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \rho _{0}=3D\alpha -\psi _{0}\beta =3D(\xi -\psi _{0}\eta )\delta ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mi>=CE=B2<!-- =CE=B2 --></mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BE<!-- =CE=BE --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mi>=CE=B7<!-- =CE=B7 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B4<!-- =CE=B4 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \rho _{0}=3D\=
alpha -\psi _{0}\beta =3D(\xi -\psi _{0}\eta )\delta ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4cbc45d7a01f23c3fa9b97f5d6ca1d20a4639e03" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:27.793ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \r=
ho _{0}=3D\alpha -\psi _{0}\beta =3D(\xi -\psi _{0}\eta )\delta ,}"></span>=
</dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=88</i><sub>0</sub></span> represent=
s the quotient and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i><sub>0</sub></span>=
 the remainder. Here the quotient and remainder are chosen so that (if nonz=
ero) the remainder has <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i>(<i>=CF=81</i><sub>0=
</sub>) &lt; <i>N</i>(<i>=CE=B2</i>)</span> for a "Euclidean function" <i>N=
</i> defined analogously to the Euclidean functions of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_domain" title=3D"Euclidean domain">Euclidean=
 domains</a> in the non-commutative case.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bgv_162-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorit=
hm#cite_note-bgv-162"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>160<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This equation shows that any common ri=
ght divisor of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CE=B1</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>=CE=B2</span> is likewise a common divisor of the remainder <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i><sub>0</sub></span>. The analogous equation for the =
left divisors would be
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \rho _{0}=3D\alpha -\beta \psi _{0}=3D\delta (\xi -\eta \psi _{0}).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B2<!-- =CE=B2 --></mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B4<!-- =CE=B4 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BE<!-- =CE=BE --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B7<!-- =CE=B7 --></mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \rho _{0}=3D\=
alpha -\beta \psi _{0}=3D\delta (\xi -\eta \psi _{0}).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c98ce45a2ec2ce08f12fba65e4c79ac36d0c4ac1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:27.793ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \r=
ho _{0}=3D\alpha -\beta \psi _{0}=3D\delta (\xi -\eta \psi _{0}).}"></span>=
</dd></dl>
<p>With either choice, the process is repeated as above until the greatest =
common right or left divisor is identified. As in the Euclidean domain, the=
 "size" of the remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i><sub>0</sub><=
/span> (formally, its Euclidean function or "norm") must be strictly smalle=
r than <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B2</sp=
an>, and there must be only a finite number of possible sizes for <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i><sub>0</sub></span>, so that the algorithm is g=
uaranteed to terminate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-entgtrg_163-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-e=
ntgtrg-163"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>161<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many results for the GCD carry over to noncommutative numbers. For e=
xample, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_identity" =
title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's identity</a> states that the=
 right <span class=3D"texhtml">gcd(<i>=CE=B1</i>, <i>=CE=B2</i>)</span> can=
 be expressed as a linear combination of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B1</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B2</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-164" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_=
note-164"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>162<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> In other words, there are numbers <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=83</span> and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=84</span> such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \Gamma _{\text{right}}=3D\sigma \alpha +\tau \beta .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93<!-- =CE=93 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>right</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>=CF=84<!-- =CF=84 --></mi>
        <mi>=CE=B2<!-- =CE=B2 --></mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \Gamma _{\tex=
t{right}}=3D\sigma \alpha +\tau \beta .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/aa8d8d3f8987285f9825f8a95255112612f8239f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:17.1ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \Gam=
ma _{\text{right}}=3D\sigma \alpha +\tau \beta .}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The analogous identity for the left GCD is nearly the same:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \Gamma _{\text{left}}=3D\alpha \sigma +\beta \tau .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93<!-- =CE=93 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>left</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B2<!-- =CE=B2 --></mi>
        <mi>=CF=84<!-- =CF=84 --></mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \Gamma _{\tex=
t{left}}=3D\alpha \sigma +\beta \tau .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7c007a58c690dcbd89cd48db55ed36d92fa9b6e8" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:15.952ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \G=
amma _{\text{left}}=3D\alpha \sigma +\beta \tau .}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>B=C3=A9zout's identity can be used to solve Diophantine equations. For i=
nstance, one of the standard proofs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Lagrange%27s_four-square_theorem" title=3D"Lagrange's four-square theo=
rem">Lagrange's four-square theorem</a>, that every positive integer can be=
 represented as a sum of four squares, is based on quaternion GCDs in this =
way.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-entgtrg_163-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#cite_note-entgtrg-163"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>161<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
